# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-a-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-a-platform] The **Chrysler A platform** was the basis for smaller rear wheel drive cars in the 1960s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-a-platform] These cars are sometimes referred to as **A-body** cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-a-platform] This list is not complete: A-platform vehicles not included on this list were sold in some countries until 1981.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-a-platform] The "A" name was reused again for the mid-size Chrysler LeBaron, Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim sedans, though this was changed to AA when Chrysler moved to two-letter names for 1990.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-a-platform] The "AA" cars lasted until 1995 when replaced by the more modern, but less popular, JA "Cloud Cars" in the same year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The **JA platform** was Chrysler's smaller complement to the LH cars which were larger than the Ks, and a direct size replacement for the last extended K cars, the Acclaim and Spirit.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] It was a mid-size front-wheel drive automobile platform that was the basis for the *Cloud Cars* – the **Chrysler Cirrus**/**Dodge Stratus**/**Plymouth Breeze** starting in 1994.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] Like the LH, it was a cab forward design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] While this platform was numerically successful, the highest volume for family cars competing against cars like the Taurus, Accord, or Camry would move to the LH platform cars, which were often classified as full-size.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The first **JA** cars were the 1995 Chrysler Cirrus and Dodge Stratus.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] These were available with either a 2.0 L 16-valve SOHC, 2.4 L 16-valve DOHC, or a Mitsubishi-designed 2.5 L 24-valve SOHC V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The Plymouth Breeze was introduced in late 1995 with most of the same options available to the other two models (minus the V6 engine).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The JA Platform was produced through to the 2000 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] A five-speed manual transmission (NV-T350) was available with the 2.0 L engine, and a four-speed automatic (A604) came with the larger engines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] AutoStick was an option for some trim levels with the 2.5 L engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] All JA sedans were built at the Chrysler Sterling Heights Assembly Plant in Sterling Heights, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] In Europe, this car became known as Chrysler Stratus, where a 2.0-liter engine with a five-speed manual (A604) and a 2.5-liter V6 engine with a four-speed automatic were available as well.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] A modified version of the JA platform called **JX** debuted in 1995 as the Chrysler Sebring convertible.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] Changes for the JX included shortening the wheelbase to 106.0 in (2,692 mm), removing the back doors and roof, stiffening the chassis to compensate for the loss of a solid top, and lengthening of the front and rear clips.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The JX also had larger rear brake drums, ceramic brake pads, and a cooler thermostat to compensate for the increased weight of the reinforcements to the unibody.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The available engines and transmissions are identical to that of the Chrysler Cirrus.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] Unlike the sedans, the convertibles were assembled in Mexico.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The platform was updated in 2000, becoming **JR**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The **Dodge Stratus** name was carried over, and the Cirrus became the **Chrysler Sebring** sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The **Chrysler Sebring** convertible was built on the JR platform as well.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The Breeze name was dropped (with the rest of Plymouth).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] Engines available were the 2.4 L I4 and the 2.7 L LH V6.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The wheelbase remained unchanged, although the track was increased slightly.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The JR sedans were built at the Sterling Heights Assembly Plant, and the convertible moved back there from Mexico.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The tooling from Sterling Heights Assembly was sold to Russian-based GAZ in 2006.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] GAZ intends to move the whole production line to a plant in Russia to build licensed JR sedans under a different name – GAZ Siber – a facelifted Chrysler Sebring of the first generation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The vehicle nameplates were shuffled with the Diamond Star Motors (DSM) coupes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] The first generation of the Avenger became the Stratus coupe, and the newly renamed Chrysler Sebring sedan now shared a name with the second generation Sebring coupe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] Both of the coupes were based on the third generation Mitsubishi Eclipse and built alongside the Eclipse.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-ja-platform] They had nothing in common with the JR platform other than the names.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The **Chrysler LeBaron** is a line of automobiles built by Chrysler from 1931 to 1941 and from 1977 to 1995.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Chrysler also used the LeBaron name for the Imperial LeBaron from 1957 to 1975.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The model was introduced in 1931, with a body manufactured by LeBaron, and competed with other luxury cars of the era, such as Lincoln and Packard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] After purchasing LeBaron with its parent Briggs Manufacturing Company, Chrysler introduced the luxury make Imperial in 1955, and sold automobiles under the name Imperial LeBaron from 1957 until 1975.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Chrysler discontinued the Imperial brand for 1976 and reintroduced the Chrysler LeBaron in 1977 to what was then Chrysler's lowest-priced model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The last Chrysler LeBaron was manufactured in 1995, to be replaced with the Cirrus and Sebring.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBaron was one of Chrysler's longest-running brands.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] LeBaron was one of the many prominent coachbuilders in the 1920s and 1930s to provide bodies for luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It was founded in Bridgeport, Connecticut, in 1920 by Thomas L.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It was later purchased by Briggs Manufacturing Company of Detroit in 1926, the major manufacturer of bodies for Ford, Chrysler, Hudson, Packard, and others, and operated as a Briggs specialist subsidiary.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] LeBaron supplied exquisite custom bodies for various car companies such as Chrysler's luxury Imperial line, Duesenberg, and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Chrysler purchased Briggs Manufacturing Company in 1953.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Two years after the Chrysler Corporation introduced the Imperial as a separate luxury division, LeBaron was designated the top-of-the-line Imperial models in 1957 through 1975.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBarons started in the 1930s during the automobile's Classic era and competed directly with the luxury brands of its day, such as Lincoln, Cadillac, and Packard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In the mid-1930s, Chrysler added a radical new "Art Deco" design shape, known as the Airflow Imperials, to the Chrysler line.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] LeBaron supplied the high-end CW series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The design features were considered advanced and perhaps ahead of their time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] However, the shape was too radical for buyer's tastes, and non-Airflow models outsold Airflows by about 3 to 1.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Raymond Dietrich, co-founder and former stylist at LeBaron, was hired in 1932 to be Chrysler's in-house stylist.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Dietrich restyled the Airflow line and moved Chryslers to more mainstream styles.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] As a result of the poor Airflow sales, Chrysler's designs became quite conservative for the next two decades.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Auto manufacturers continued to build up their in-house styling departments and bodyworks.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] LeBaron thus became less important to most of its customers for design ideas and bodies.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Toward the late 1930s, LeBaron/Briggs built more bodies for Chrysler and fewer for Ford.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Chrysler became their biggest customer, with additional bodies built for Packard, Hudson, and Graham-Paige.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] During the late 1930s and early 1940s, the LeBaron name and division became less critical for Briggs, although it remained a division of Briggs until the Chrysler buy-out in 1953.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For the 1955 model year, Chrysler Corporation spun off Imperial as a separate make and division, its flagship luxury brand, taking its name from the original Chrysler Imperial series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Intended as a direct competitor for Cadillac, Lincoln, and Packard, Imperial was a completely distinct vehicle make/brand that did not use the Chrysler nameplate.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Through the existence of the division, Imperial used two nameplates alongside a nameless base model (Imperial Custom, from 1960–1963).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Its mid-range line was the Imperial Crown, with the flagship line branded as the Imperial LeBaron (in deference to the coachbuilder); Southampton was a sub-designation applied for pillarless hardtop bodystyles.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In June 1975, Chrysler retired the Imperial brand in response to declining sales of the marque; the Imperial LeBaron was repackaged for 1976 as the Chrysler New Yorker Brougham.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1977, the LeBaron model nameplate made its return after a year's hiatus.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Released in response to the Cadillac Seville and Lincoln Versailles, the 1977 Chrysler LeBaron was the smallest vehicle ever marketed under the Chrysler brand at the time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] While Cadillac and Lincoln offered its mid-size lines solely as four-door sedans, Chrysler also offered a two-door LeBaron coupe; for 1978, the Town & Country station wagon joined the model line.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Sharing its body with the Dodge Diplomat and Plymouth Caravelle, the LeBaron used the Chrysler M platform on a 112.7 in (2,863 mm) wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A new generation of the F platform introduced by the Dodge Aspen/Plymouth Volaré, the LeBaron sedan and wagon shared much of its roofline with the Aspen/Volaré; sharing its wheelbase with the sedan, the LeBaron coupe was fitted with a sleeker roofline than its Volaré counterpart.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] While visibly similar, the LeBaron was fitted with its own hood, trunklid, and front and rear fascia panels.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Both platforms shared a common powertrain lineup, with a standard 225 cu in (3.7 L) Slant Six; 318 cu in (5.2 L) or 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engines are optional.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A three-speed Torqueflite automatic transmission was offered with all three engines, though a four-speed manual overdrive transmission was offered with the 225 and 318 engines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1980, the LeBaron underwent a mid-cycle revision.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The exterior underwent several aerodynamic enhancements, featuring sharper-edged front corners, and a narrower radiator-style grille (similar to the 1975 Imperial, debuting a design used by Chrysler into the early 1990s).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The roofline of the sedan was revised for aerodynamic upgrades; a squared-off look ended its design commonality with the Aspen/Volaré; the coupe adopted a more formal profile.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] To position the model line upmarket, Chrysler introduced the limited-edition "Fifth Avenue" option package for the four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A conversion by American Sunroof Corporation, the Fifth Avenue featured a padded vinyl roof covering the quarter glass of the rear doors and interior trim upgrades.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In response to the discontinuation of the Volaré after 1980, Chrysler introduced a police-equipment option package for the LeBaron for 1981, sold alongside the Chrysler Newport and R-platform Plymouth Gran Fury.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1982, Chrysler replaced all three vehicles as it moved the Gran Fury to the M platform (joining the Dodge Diplomat), offering the option for the Diplomat and Gran Fury until Chrysler ended production of the M platform after 1989.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1982, the LeBaron moved to the front-wheel drive Chrysler K platform, where it was the upscale brand's lowest-priced offering.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It was initially available in just sedan and coupe versions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In early 1982, it was released in a convertible version, bringing to the market the first factory-built open-topped domestic vehicle since the 1976 Cadillac Eldorado.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A station wagon version called the **Town and Country** was also added.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A unique Town and Country convertible was also made from 1983 until 1986 with a 1,105 total produced, which, like the wagon, featured simulated wood paneling that made it resemble the original 1940s Town and Country.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] This model also offered the well-equipped Mark Cross option package for the latter years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Despite being mechanically similar to the Aries and Reliant, its fascias closely resembled the larger E-body sedans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] This generation featured Chrysler's Electronic Voice Alert, a computerized voice that warned drivers about various conditions with phrases such as "A door is ajar" or "Your engine oil pressure is low".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBaron was facelifted for 1986, receiving rounder front and rear ends to improve aerodynamics.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A landau padded top replaced the sedan's full vinyl roof.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The instrumentation cluster was revised from a rectangle speedometer and fuel gauge with a message center to round gauges similar to the Reliant/Aries but with an argent surround for a more upscale appearance.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Coupes and convertibles were dropped for 1987, replaced by the all-new J-body LeBaron released that year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The sedan and wagon continued with minor changes until 1988.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A new digital dashboard replaced the analog gauges for a more modern appearance.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A larger LeBaron sedan based on the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim would arrive for the 1990 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The 1985 **LeBaron GTS** was a somewhat different car than the standard LeBaron and was based on the Chrysler H platform.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It was available at the same time as the Cadillac Cimarron as a luxury-brand model while offering a similar level of equipment to the small Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] As a 5-door hatchback still derived from the K-car, the GTS (and the similar Dodge Lancer) was more of a performance vehicle than the softer-tuned K-car LeBaron sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In base configuration, the car was powered by Chrysler's 2.2 liter inline-4 engine, later replaced by a 2.5 L TBI version generating 100 hp (75 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] A turbocharged 2.2 L engine producing 146 hp (109 kW) was also available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The GTS moniker was dropped for 1989, the final year of this vehicle's production, after the K-based LeBaron sedan was discontinued after 1988.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] After some years of absence, Chrysler officially started offering some models under its brand on the European market from April 1988.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] One of them was the "Chrysler GTS", which was a rebadged version of the Dodge Lancer ES.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] After discontinuing the first generation LeBaron coupe and convertible in 1986, Chrysler released a new LeBaron for 1987, built on the J platform (a K platform derivative) and available as a coupe or convertible.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBaron was equipped with a trip and fuel economy computer as well as full instrumentation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In Mexico, these models were marketed as the Chrysler Phantom.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1990, the LeBaron's interior was refreshed, featuring an all new dashboard, gauge cluster, door panels, and center console design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] All of the new components were designed to be smoother and more flowing than the comparatively boxy 1987-89 interior style, making it more in tune with the "aero" revolution of the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The 1992 LeBaron coupes and convertibles could be ordered with a new "sport package", which featured a monochrome appearance including body-colored grille, accent stripe, and decklid logo.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The package also included 14-inch "lace" style wheelcovers and a black strip below the taillights in place of chrome, with special blacked-out window moldings on coupe models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In 1992 for the 1993 model year, the LeBaron received a slight facelift.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The hidden headlamps of the 1987-1992 models were deleted in favor of less costly flush-mounted replaceable-bulb headlamps, new wheel styles were made available, and all models got the amber rear turn signals introduced on the deluxe 1992 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1994, a passenger side airbag became standard on all models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Also new for 1994 was the "Bright LX" decor package which included a "bright" chrome grille, "bright" chrome badging, and "bright" chrome molding inserts, as opposed to being body-colored on the GTC.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The available engines were a naturally aspirated 2.5 L and a turbocharged 2.2 and 2.5 L versions of Chrysler's inline-four, and the 3.0 L Mitsubishi V6 making a 141 hp (105 kW) in this application.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The turbocharged engines were dropped from the lineup in 1992 for the 1993 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For the last two model years, the 3.0 was the only available engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The convertible was discontinued after 1995, to make way for the new Chrysler Sebring coupes and convertibles, for 1995 and 1996 respectively.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Throughout its lifetime, the LeBaron convertible/coupe was available in a number of trim levels.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For its first year, the LeBaron was available in *Highline* and *Premium*, typical Chrysler trims at the time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The number of trims grew, peaking in 1990, with six available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] After that, the number decreased until just two trim levels remained for 1995.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBaron coupe/convertible was part of Chrysler's export push and was regularly available across Europe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Springs and shocks were somewhat firmer on European-market cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The initial European lineup was made up of the naturally aspirated 2.5 and the turbocharged 2.2; both were offered with a 5-speed manual or a 3-speed automatic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In mid-1988, the turbocharged 2.2 was partially replaced by the 2.5 Turbo, with power slightly lower at 146 PS (107 kW; 144 hp).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The 2.2 Turbo received an intercooler, which boosted maximum power to 177 PS (130 kW; 175 hp).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Called the LeBaron GTC, it was not offered with the automatic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Both turbo versions were discontinued during 1989; the 2.5 Turbo returned (only with the five-speed manual transmission) some time during 1990.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The new version produces 155 PS (114 kW; 153 hp) at 4700 rpm, but it was discontinued yet again in 1991.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The 3.0-liter Mitsubishi V6 engine was introduced to European buyers in mid-1989, and was only available with the four-speed automatic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It produces somewhat less power than the American models; 136 PS (100 kW; 134 hp) at 5200 rpm.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The top speed was 182 km/h (113 mph) and the 0–100 km/h (62 mph) sprint took 10.8 seconds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] After the 2.5 Turbo was discontinued in 1991, the V6 remained the only regular option until the LeBaron Coupé/Convertible ended European sales in mid-1994.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Several ARCA (one tier down from *NASCAR* cup racing) teams built *LeBaron* based race cars (supported by a revitalized *Chrysler* Direct Connection performance parts division) and ran them from 1988 until 1998.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The last LeBaron sedan was built on the front wheel drive AA platform, another K derivative, as junior level sedan to the more upscale New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] It offered rebadged versions under the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim nameplates, and the three differed mostly in detail and trim choices, as well as the European Chrysler Saratoga and Chrysler New Yorker in Mexico (1990-1994).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Theoretically, as historically was the case in this era versus its Dodge and Plymouth corporate siblings, the LeBaron was marketed as the luxury version, reflecting the Chrysler brand's flagship status.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] In reality, however, there was considerable overlap amongst the three in available trim, equipment and features.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Launched in a single trim, the top-line LeBaron Landau model offered a padded vinyl half-roof with smaller "formal" backlight, as well as unique button-tufted bench seats.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] All LeBaron sedans came with a standard driver's side airbag, and could seat up to six passengers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Due to Chrysler's efforts to refocus the Plymouth brand at the value end and to expand the Chrysler brand's sales, for 1992 the Plymouth Acclaim would lose its mid-range LE and top-line LX trims.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] They were instead added to the LeBaron lineup as the base and LX trims, below the former standard trim, which was now called Landau.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LX, which retained the Acclaim's taillights instead of the LeBaron's full-width treatment was available for 1992 only, and now the only model to feature the V6 as standard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] For 1993, the LeBaron sedan received new rear lights, which incorporated the reversing lamps previously located in the bumper fascia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] Trim levels were reduced to just the base model, renamed LE, and the luxury Landau.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The LeBaron sedan was discontinued on May 18, 1994, while the Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim continued production until December 21, 1994.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The Chrysler LeBaron was replaced by the "Cloud Car" Chrysler Cirrus.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration rated the LeBaron a 4 out of 5 for driver side and a 3 out of 5 for passenger side frontal impact occupant protection.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] M and K-platform cars were assembled in the Toluca, Mexico facility.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The M-platform LeBaron was sold in Mexico from the 1977 to the 1982 model years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The K-car LeBaron was also produced in Toluca and was sold for the 1983 through 1987 model years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] There were no K-platform convertibles offered from the factory.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-lebaron] The Mexican AA-body Chrysler LeBaron 4-door sedan was called the New Yorker (all of them with Landau roof), and the "K" body (slightly shorter) was reserved for the 4-door LeBaron's, which were sold in two trim levels, one with Landau roof and leather, and the other one without those two options.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The **Chrysler Saratoga** is an automobile built by Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The nameplate was used from 1939 to 1952 and from 1957 to 1960 in the U.S. market, in Canada through 1965, and in Europe from 1989 to 1995.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In the beginning, it was introduced as a sport luxury model, using the Straight Eight engine from the Chrysler New Yorker which was more formal, and the Imperial which had graduated to special order limousine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga was introduced one year after the luxurious New Yorker and was well equipped, wearing the Chrysler nameplate.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was initially more expensive than the New Yorker, then marketing changes repositioned the Saratoga more modestly as the Imperial took the top of the Chrysler hierarchy followed by the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Items that were standard equipment such as power windows, power locks, power steering, power brakes, power adjustable front seat and air conditioning on the New Yorker were initially available on the Saratoga, then as years progressed became standard on the Saratoga.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] As it maintained its high performance image for Chrysler, it was used to introduce the 331 cu in (5.4 L) overhead valve Hemi V8 in 1951.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was discontinued in 1953 initially when the New Yorker, and, later the 1955 Chrysler 300 took over as the performance models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was reintroduced from 1957 until 1965 as a junior model to the Chrysler 300 and was available as a sedan and priced lower.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1989, the nameplate was reused only in Europe as a rebadged Dodge Spirit available with a 3.0 V6 and a 5-speed manual transmission until 1995.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was named for Saratoga Springs, New York, and is home to the Saratoga Race Course, a thoroughbred horse racing track.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga nameplate first appeared in 1939 and shared the 125 in (3,175 mm) wheelbase and the 323.5 cu in (5.3 L) Chrysler Straight-8 with the C-23 Imperial and C-23 New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] At its introduction, it was Chrysler's second most expensive models, above that of the Imperial and the New Yorker but below the Series C-24 Imperial Custom sedans and limousines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was only offered as a Club Coupe or the four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Prices listed for the 1939 Saratoga were US$1,495 ($34,603 in 2025 dollars ) for the Club Coupe and US$1,443 ($33,400 in 2025 dollars ) for the four-door Sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Saratogas were introduced as a "sports luxury", with leather and Bedford cord upholstery, with an optional sun roof, while the optional, high compression aluminum cylinder head was available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Chrysler had a history of producing race car products going back to the Chrysler Six that was entered in the 1925 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1940, Chrysler updated the Series C-23 with the Series C-26 and all came with a 128.5 in (3,264 mm) wheelbase and the 323.5 cu in (5.3 L) Chrysler Straight-8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga became a sports luxury trim package as a sedan only, and in two interior configurations, standard and sport formal.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The latter had a glass privacy partition in the front seat back which could be lowered as found in limousines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The all-new Chrysler Traveler was the economy model, the New Yorker was luxury focused, and New Yorker Highlander models came with tartan interior.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Fluid Drive was offered for the first time, mated to a three-speed manual transmission along with Cruise and Climb overdrive.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1941, the Saratoga was assigned to Chrysler's Series C30 and was demoted to the bottom of the eight-cylinder series, replacing the Traveler.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Body styles offered expanded to include a business coupe, club coupe, two-door sedan and four-door Town Sedan, as well as the six-window sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga offered Fluid Drive and the eight-cylinder version of Vacamatic which consisted of a three-speed transmission mated to an overdrive unit.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1942 the Series C-36 Saratoga was again available only with an eight-cylinder engine along with the same transmission selections as in 1941.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Selection of body styles also remained as in 1941.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga nameplate returned for 1946, positioned as Chrysler's second expensive eight-cylinder model below the New Yorker, in a full array of body styles shared with the New Yorker wheelbase, sharing the die-cast grille with all Chrysler products.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The body styles available were the two-door three-passenger coupe, two-door six-passenger Brougham Sedan, two-door six-passenger Club Coupe and the four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga was related to the six-cylinder Chrysler Windsor with the same longer wheelbase, along with the Chrysler Royal and the DeSoto Custom.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Prices listed for the Saratoga averaged at US$1,826 ($30,148 in 2025 dollars ) and 1,544 were recorded to have been manufactured in 1946.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Annual styling changes were almost non-existent between 1946 and the "First Series" 1949 Chryslers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Distinguishing a Chrysler model was limited to a nameplate attached on the front fender just below the engine hood, interior upholstery and standard features installed that were optional on other models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga offered pile fabric or broadcloth upholstery, rubber floor covering for the front passengers with a carpeted rear passenger compartment, turn signals, an electric clock, two-speed electric windshield wipers, and an illuminated trunk compartment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The upscale Club Coupe offered carpeting for the front passengers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The interior trim and upholstery was less elaborate than the New Yorker while the Saratoga shared the 127.5 in (3,238 mm) wheelbase, straight eight engine and standard equipment but shared an appearance used on the Chrysler Royal which was only available with a six-cylinder engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Because of government restrictions on manufacturer source goods, Chrysler offered white steel "beauty rings" on its car wheels to give the appearance of wide white wall tires.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] White wall tires as an option returned in 1947.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Fluid Drive continued but the four speed semi-automatic, called Presto-Matic was now offered.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The years initially after the war were a sellers market, as customers replaced vehicles they needed to maintain during the war.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] When production resumed, Chrysler had very little resistance selling every car they made as customers wanted something new and modern.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1948, Chrysler increased prices across the board so as to invest in new appearances for the next product cycle.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The average price for a Saratoga was US$2,244 ($30,070 in 2025 dollars ) and 2,121 were recorded to have been manufactured in 1948.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Also starting in 1948 the Maywood, California factory began production until the mid-1970s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The semi-automatic was now called Prestomatic on Chryslers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Saratoga production for 1949 came to 2,275 vehicles in total, and the average list price for the Saratoga was US$2,461 ($33,301 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Model year 1949 and later Chryslers had a padded dash as a safety feature, the first in an American mass production car.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1950 models received new grilles, taillights and a larger rear window.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The 1951 Saratoga was introduced well into the model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In Chrysler's model numbering system it was designated C55.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The two numerical didgets don't correspond to model years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1951 the Saratoga was built on the shorter 125.5 in (3,188 mm) wheelbase shared with the flathead six powered Windsor, but offered the Chrysler's famed 331 cu in (5.4 L) Hemi V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Power drum brakes were standard with v8 engines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Also offered as an option was Hydraguide power steering, an industry first, and Fluid Torque Drive, a true torque converter in place of Fluid Drive's fluid coupling.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The engine was used in the Cunningham C-2R where the C-2R debuted at 1951 24 Hours of Le Mans, continuing a tradition of racing Chrysler engines at LeMans which began in 1925.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1951 and 1952 Saratoga 2 door Club Coupe models were the lightest body styles with the 180 horse power Hemi V8's and were used in road racing and stock car racing.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In the 1951 La Carrera Panamericana, a cross country rally from the northern border of Mexico to the southern border, a Saratoga driven by Bill Sterling came in third behind two Ferraris.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Minnesota based outboard boat motor manufacturer Mercury Marine owned by Carl Kiekhaefer raced a pair of Saratogas in the grueling multiday race in 1951 and 1952.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Average speeds approached 110 miles an hour in some segments and a Saratoga had the top average speed in one segment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Model selection also increased for 1951 with a wagon plus eight-passenger sedan and on the 139.5 in (3,543 mm) wheelbase added.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] This combination of the shorter, lighter Six body and the powerful new V-8 put the new Hemi Saratoga in the same performance league as the Olds Rocket 88, but was the quicker car.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1951 proved to be a great year with 34,806 cars built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Most were six-passenger, four-door sedans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Two-door Club Coupes, four-door station wagons, and eight-passenger, four-door sedans were relatively rare.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Two forward facing jump seats ahead of the back seat provided the extra seating in the latter model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Unlike the Windsor, which offered an eight-passenger sedan as well as a limousine, no 1951-1952 Saratoga limousines were built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] V8 limousine customers were only offered the Crown Imperial.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The difference between an 8-passenger sedan verses a limousine was the presence of a glass divider and all leather seating surfaces in the front compartment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1952 brought new tail lamps with the backup lamps moved to the same housing as the tail lamps.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Due to the Korean War, production dropped to 17,401 for the 1952 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] A further 1,300 Saratoga models were built in Canada, the first eight-cylinder Chryslers to roll out of the Windsor plant since 1937.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1952 Model year Chryslers suffered from a war strategic materials shortage and the pot metal trim was painted silver rather than chromed.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1953 the Saratoga was discontinued, and the Saratoga's sports luxury duties were initially given to the New Yorker in 1953 until the performance coupe Chrysler 300 was introduced in 1955.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Chrysler reused the Saratoga nameplate in 1957 as part of its "Forward Look" styling by Virgil Exner.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga maintained its position between the entry-level Windsor and top New Yorkers models, and was related to the DeSoto Firedome, but received trim upgrades and better appointments inside the passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The tradition of adding the Newport as a suffix to the model name continued and a four-door hardtop was added.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The base V8 in the Saratoga was a cast-iron 354 cu in (5.80 L) "Poly head" V8 shared with the Windsor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Chrysler's highly praised Hemi was available on the Saratoga and Windsor as an option and a larger 392 cubic inch with dual four-barrel carburetors that was standard on the more upscale Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Early 1957 models featured dual headlights, with quad-headlights as an option where permitted by state law.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] By the model year's end all Saratogas were outfitted with quad headlights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Saratoga production for 1957 came to 37,196 vehicles and the average list price for the Saratoga was US$3,768 ($43,194 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1958, all Windsors were shifted to the 122 inch Dodge chassis, and used a modified front end design based in part on Dodge's front clip - this was especially evident around the Windsor's headlights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratogas continued to be based on the longer 126 inch wheelbase using the New Yorker body and was again available in three body styles – four-door sedan, four-door hardtop, and two-door hardtop coupe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In Canada, the 1957–1958 Saratoga was sold as the Windsor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The American Windsor was not sold in Canada although Windsor Town and Country station wagons were imported.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1959, the Saratoga remained on the longer Chrysler wheelbase and in the same three models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga was sold as the Saratoga in Canada this year, sharing its interior with the Canadian-built DeSoto Firedome.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1959 the Saratoga got the new RB V8 engine, although it was the Chrysler-only 383-cid in 1959 and 1960.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Canadian-built 1959–1960 Saratogas used the B block 383 as used by Dodge and DeSoto.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In its final year in the U.S., the 1960 Chrysler Saratoga was based wholly on the New Yorker body shell, less New Yorker trimmings, and again offered in three body styles – four-door sedan, four-door hardtop, and two-door hardtop coupe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Some 15,525 1960 Chrysler Saratogas rolled off the assembly line.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Whilst the Saratoga was discontinued in the U.S. market after the 1960 model year, it remained an active nameplate in Canada from 1961 through 1965.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1961, Chrysler added the Newport as its entry-level model for the American market, positioned below the Windsor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It used a name which in 1961 was commonly associated with Chrysler's expensive hardtops in the early and mid-1950s to take the market segment left open when the manufacturer's DeSoto brand was canceled.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In 1961, in the US, the mid-range Saratoga was discontinued, with the Windsor name elevated to the mid-level position, and in 1962 the Windsor was replaced by the introduction of the 300, a non-"letter series" performance-oriented luxury sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The 1961 Saratoga shared a futuristic semi-circular domed instrument cluster Chrysler called the AstraDome, which housed the speedometer and all gauges in one location with the Chrysler 300, Newport, Windsor, and New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The cluster's appearance was compared to a gum ball machine, and the gauges at night could be viewed with electroluminescent lighting Chrysler called "Panelescent Light", a feature shared with all Chrysler, Dodge, Plymouth, DeSoto, and Imperial vehicles starting in 1960.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] In Canada, the Saratoga continued on through to 1965, with the Windsor line remaining as the base model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Thus the Canadian 1961 Saratoga was basically the US' Windsor, with Saratoga nameplates, on the 122 inch wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1962, the new 300 was not offered on the Canadian market, but rather the Saratoga.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The grille was shared with the Newport/Windsor while the side trim was from the American Newport.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Model offering remained 4-door sedan and hardtop as well as the 2-door hardtop.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] New bodies appeared for 1963 with the Canadian Saratoga using the same grille and trim as the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 300, only with "Saratoga 300" nameplates, as the series was now called.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Body styles remained the same and this year the 300 convertible was imported.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Although the American 1964 300 continued to use the 1963 headlamp rings, the Canadian Saratoga 300 used the headlamp treatment of the Newport/Windsor, and had 300 side trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The American 300 convertible continued to be an import.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] 1965 brought completely new "C" bodies on a 124-inch wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Again, the Canadian Saratoga 300 was identical to the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] This was the last year for a Saratoga sold in North America.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] For 1966 the mid-range Chrysler series in Canada was sold as the 300, except it used Newport/Windsor taillamps.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The same three models continued, but this year the American 300 convertible and two-door hardtop were imported and marketed as the Sport 300.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The Saratoga name was revived in 1989 when Chrysler rebadged its Dodge Spirit sedan for export to Europe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Marketing of this Saratoga was officially discontinued in 1993, but the Saratoga continued being built and exported, and parts unique to it continued being catalogued through the 1995 end of A-body production.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] It was manufactured at the Sterling Heights Assembly factory.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] These export-market Saratogas were not simply Dodge Spirits with different nameplates.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] All Saratogas featured front bucket seats.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Starting in 1993, the Saratoga was available with leather seats and other luxury equipment not provided in the North American market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Most 1993 and later Saratogas were equipped with the V6/4-speed automatic powertrain.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] All Saratogas were equipped with the highest-specification suspension and brake systems made by Chrysler for the A-body.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] The last Saratogas, sold in 1994 and 1995, were based on the US-market Chrysler LeBaron Sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] They can be identified by additional fender chrome and an "LE" badge on the trunklid.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] These models were all equipped with the 3.0 liter Mitsubishi V6, the A604 automatic transmission, leather seats and air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-saratoga] Saratoga production ended on December 9, 1994, and was replaced with the Chrysler Stratus.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The **Chrysler Valiant** is a full-size car which was sold by Chrysler Australia between 1962 and 1981.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Initially a rebadged locally assembled Plymouth Valiant from the United States, from the second generation launched in 1963, the Valiant was fully manufactured in Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It was sold locally but also in New Zealand and South Africa, with smaller numbers also exported to South-East Asia and the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Parent company Chrysler made a substantial investment in Australian manufacturing facilities by establishing operations in South Australia with an assembly plant at Tonsley Park in 1964 and an engine foundry at Lonsdale in 1968.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant thus established its position as the third of the "Big 3" Australian-made vehicles behind the Holden Kingswood and Ford Falcon.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Australian Valiant was built on the North American A-body platform but with many parts and components from Australian suppliers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Apart from a sedan and wagon body style, 1965 saw the introduction of a commercial utility that was badged the **Wayfarer** and later exported to South Africa as the **Rustler**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Greater differentiation from the donor car crept in over time, particularly since the VE series, which was embraced by the Australian motoring press and won the 1967 *Wheels* magazine Car of the Year award.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VF series of 1969 and the VG of 1970 departed even further from its North American donor both in terms of styling and performance—with the latter series introducing the *Hemi-6* engine that replaced the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Moreover, Australia continued to produce a station wagon model, called the **Safari**, even after this body style was discontinued for North America.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Beginning in 1971, the VH series saw Chrysler Australia develop the entire lineup locally including the Charger.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Local design and production continued until the CM series of 1979, which marked the end of local production in 1981, after the takeover of operations by Mitsubishi Motors Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] After the Plymouth Valiant turned out to be a success in the United States (starting with its 1959 introduction), Chrysler released Australia's first locally assembled Valiant, the RV1 (R-series).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It was officially unveiled by South Australia's Premier, Sir Thomas Playford, in January 1962 and was assembled at Chrysler's Mile End facility.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 (or R Series) Valiant was an instant success.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Not everyone was taken instantly by the car's styling, but the general consensus was that the car had a modern, almost space age quality about it.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Also notable was the Valiant's performance with 145 brake horsepower (108 kW) from the 225 *Slant-6* engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This was a lot of power compared to the competing Holdens and Fords, which offered only 75 bhp (56 kW) and 90 bhp (67 kW) SAE respectively.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Standard transmission in the RV1 was a floor-shifted three-speed manual with a non-synchro first gear.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A button-operated three-speed TorqueFlite automatic was optional.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Other options included a heater-demister unit, as well as a "Moparmatic" deluxe pushbutton transistor radio.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 Valiant was the first Australian car to come with an alternator instead of a generator, and instead of coil springs, the Valiant came with torsion bar suspension.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Brakes were hydraulic 9" drums front and rear.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 had a simulated spare wheel outline on the bootlid, but the spare wheel was actually under the floor of the boot.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In March 1962, Chrysler replaced the American 1961-model R Valiant with the American 1962 SV1 (S Series) Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The SV1 used the same body shell as the RV1, with cosmetic changes including the deletion of the simulated spare wheel on the bootlid, and round tail lamps replacing the R-model's cat-eye shaped ones.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] There was a revised radiator grille and new exterior trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Mechanical changes included relocation of the manual transmission shifter to the steering column, new ball joints, and a new gear-reduction starter motor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] 10,009 SV1 Valiants were sold, of which 5,496 were automatics and 4,513 were manuals.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] On 30 May 1963, Chrysler Australia produced the first fully Australian manufactured Valiant, the **AP5**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In February of that year, Chrysler Australia had begun work on its new $36 million Tonsley Park facility in South Australia, where it could boost annual production to 50 thousand cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new plant produced its first Valiants on 31 March 1964.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The AP5 ("AP" for *Australian Production*) was an entirely new design with only the four doors, windscreen, and front guards shared with its North American counterpart.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Initial cars retained the left-hand-drive wiper pattern but this was soon changed to a RHD layout.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6* driveline was retained, but the AP5 was considerably more straightforward in styling than its R- and S-model antecedents.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] With high local content and specifications optimised for local conditions, this new Valiant strengthened the brand's position in the marketplace.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A new upmarket **Regal** version was included in the range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In November 1963 an AP5 **Safari** station wagon was released.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Total production of the AP5 range amounted to 49,440 vehicles.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In March 1965, the AP5 was supplanted by the **AP6**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The body shell was the same, but there was a new grille on the theme of the 1964 North American Plymouth Barracuda, and there was new trim inside and out.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The automatic transmission was no longer controlled by pushbuttons, but instead by a conventional shift lever.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 also included other new features such as self-adjusting brakes and acrylic enamel paint, at the time the most advanced auto finish available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 model range included the **Valiant Wayfarer**, the first Valiant-based coupe utility to be built by Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 was the first Australian-built Valiant to be offered with a V8 engine – the 273 cu in (4.47 L) LA V8, introduced in American Valiants in 1964, and released in Australia in August 1965.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The engine developed 180 brake horsepower (130 kW) and pushed the Valiant to a top speed of 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The V8 was only available as a model in its own right, the V8 Valiant, which had a vinyl-covered roof, individual bucket seats, floor console mounted automatic shift lever and two-tone steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6'*s camshaft was also slightly upgraded for improved torque by dint of increased duration and lift.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler Australia had difficulty meeting demand, with the Valiant being built at Tonsley Park at a maximum rate of 200 cars per eight-hour shift.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Customers had to wait up to four months for delivery of a new AP6.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VC Valiant was introduced in March 1966 and, although underneath it was basically the same car as the preceding AP6 Series, the body was extensively restyled giving the illusion of being longer and lower.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The modern new design was highlighted by sharp, squared-off edges and corners clearly influenced by Chrysler in the United States.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The front now had a full-width horizontal grille while the rear was also much squarer with vertical taillights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The range of models again consisted of the Valiant standard or Regal sedan, standard or Safari Regal wagon and Wayfarer utility.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] They featured higher standard equipment levels as well as new safety features, such as optional disc brakes on V8 models, which were named 'Valiant V8/Safari V8' and were essentially Regal models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In total, Chrysler Australia built 65,634 VC Series models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This Valiant was an all-new design introduced in October 1967, based on the North American platform, which had a 108 in (2,700 mm) wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The bonnet and guards were shared with the also-new 1967 North American Dodge Dart, with other styling cues otherwise inherited from the North American Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The car featured slightly larger body dimensions and greater interior space than the preceding VC Series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The roofline was also flattened out and the rear window was given a concave profile.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Higher levels of standard equipment were featured and two engine options became available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The basic *Slant-6* was retained with its 145 bhp (108 kW) rating, but a new 2-barrel carbureted version was released with output of 160 bhp (120 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The 273 V8 was also improved and made available across the entire Valiant range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] All models benefited from additional safety features (some compulsory under new Australian Design Rules, or ADRs) such as dual circuit brakes with a tandem master cylinder, double sided safety rims, front seat belts and front power disc brakes on V8 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VE range consisted of Valiant & Valiant Regal sedans, Valiant Safari & Valiant Regal Safari station wagons and Valiant, Valiant Wayfarer & Dodge utilities, the latter being a lower-priced version of the Valiant utility.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The flagship model followed on from the AP6 and VC V8 theme, being similarly equipped with bucket seats, floor shift automatic, and vinyl roof all standard, but was given the new name "VIP" to distinguish it from other models, since the V8 engine option was made available across the range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It also shared the 3 'sergeant stripes' of the VC V8 on the rear quarter panel.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The biggest accolade for the VE Valiant was *Wheels* "Car of the Year" in 1967 – the first for Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In March 1969, the VE was replaced by the **VF** model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new car shared its middle section with the previous VE Valiant, but there was new front and rear styling.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new front end featured a horizontally convex grille, replacing the VE's concave design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The front indicators were placed at the top leading edge of the front guards rather than in a more conventional location in the grille or front bumper.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This allowed the VF's front bumper to be thinner and less prominent, which made the single round headlights look larger, and the front end appeared more aggressive as a result.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Valiant Regal models were once again available, and the VF range also saw the introduction of the **Valiant Regal 770** and an upgraded VIP model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VF VIP was introduced two months after the Valiant range and was no longer a Valiant V.I.P. but was now marketed as a **Chrysler VIP**, in sedan form only.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It offered a stretched (112 inches or 2,800 millimetres) wheelbase, with longer rear doors than the Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] As with previous model changes, the VF boasted even more safety features including a padded instrument panel and energy absorbing steering column.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A larger 5.2 L (318 cu in) version of the LA V8 replaced the 273, taking the V8's top speed to 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options remained the same: three-speed manual or three-speed TorqueFlite automatic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The most significant introduction to the VF range was the all new two-door Valiant Hardtop – essentially, a North American Dodge Dart coupé with the Australian Valiant front sheetmetal and interior trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] At over 5,000 mm (200 in), it is the longest coupe ever built in Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Released six months after the other VF Valiants in September 1969, it was available in Valiant, Valiant Regal and Valiant Regal 770 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In mid 1969, Chrysler released a fast four-door named **Valiant Pacer**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A low-cost, high-power version of the bread-and-butter Valiant sedan, the Pacer featured a high-performance six-cylinder engine and three-speed manual gearbox with floor shifter.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Despite a lack of exterior chrome, the VF Pacer stood out with its red and black grille, simulated-mag wheel hub caps, special body striping, 'Pacer 225' decals, and choice of "Wild Blue", "Wild Red", or "Wild Yellow" exterior colours.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The sparsely trimmed interior featured high back bucket seats, and distinctive black on white instrument dials with a dash-top-mounted tachometer.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although lacking the V8 of its rivals, the Pacer could reach almost 180 km/h (112 mph) and, at $2798, was $400 cheaper than the base GTS Monaro.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer was powered by a special version of the trusty 225 *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] With two-barrel carburettor, high-flow exhaust system, and 9.3:1 compression ratio, it produced 175 bhp (130 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Standard brakes were finned, servo-assisted drum brakes all round, although most buyers opted for the optional front discs.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Underneath was Valiant's basic torsion bar suspension, lowered by 125 mm (5 in) to improve handling and with a front anti-sway bar fitted.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A 'Sure-Grip' limited-slip differential with either 3.23:1 or 2.92:1 ratios was optional.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Contemporary road testers were mostly full of praise for the Pacer, noting there were few cars that could match it on a performance for price basis.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] *Modern Motor* (May, 1969) took a VF Pacer sedan to 60 mph (97 km/h) in a respectable 10.5 seconds, the 1⁄4 mile (400 m) in 17.5 seconds and topped out at 111 mph (179 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In 1969, Chrysler's market share reached 13.7%.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In total, 52,944 VF Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] August 1970 saw the introduction of another facelifted version of the VE/VF bodystyle in the **VG** Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VG's most noticeable difference was the use of rectangular headlamps instead of the traditional round ones (except on VIP models, which used quad round headlamps).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The guard-top indicator location was carried over from the VF.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The grille was a horizontal, single-plane item, and the taillamps were revised and wrapped around to the body side.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Sedan, Wagon, Ute and Hardtop body styles were offered once again as well as the same luxury levels as before.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The biggest announcement to come with the VG Valiant was of the all new *Hemi-6 engine*, replacing the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new engine was introduced as a 245 cu in (4.0 L) unit with quasi-hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The "*Hemi*" name was already legendary in America with Chrysler's use of the *Hemi V8*, hence Chrysler Australia's marketing leverage for its 6-cylinder offering.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The sporty Pacer sedan was available again, but whereas the VF Pacer was only offered with the one power output, the new VG Pacer offered 3 different versions of the new 245 *Hemi-6* engine, though Chrysler Australia didn't publish any power output figures for the Pacers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The standard Pacer had a 2-barrel carburettor and produced 185 bhp (138 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] **Option E31** produced 195 bhp (145 kW) and included a two-barrel carburettor, higher-performance camshaft, smaller fan, and windage tray.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] **Option E35** included a 4-barrel carburettor, high-performance camshaft, heavy-duty engine bearings, a dual-plate clutch, torque-limiting engine mount strut, and the ordinary Pacer-spec transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VG series Pacers were also the first and last to be offered in the Hardtop body style, of which three were optioned with the E31 package and three were optioned with E35 package.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] No VG Pacer Hardtops were available with the E34 option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Due to Chrysler Australia's policy (local content law/government law) of using only locally produced components, and the unavailability of a local four-speed gearbox, the Pacer was offered with only a three-speed floor shift manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A total of 46,374 VG Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler released the VH Valiant range in June 1971.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VH was designed by Chrysler in the United States with input from Australian engineers to be an Australia-only model range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It was a major change from the preceding VG range – these were larger cars, styled to look even larger than they were.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The grille treatment on the new VH range was a direct design descendant from the US Mopars with the central recessed area for grille and headlamps, surrounded by uninterrupted trim on the outer leading edge of the whole assembly.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The rectangular headlamps were carried over from the VG model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The model range of the VH Valiant was quite extensive, starting with the new entry-level Valiant Ranger, and progressing to Valiant Ranger XL, Valiant Pacer, Valiant Regal, and Valiant Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Carried over from the VG range, the basic *Hemi-6* 245ci engine was standard equipment for Ranger XL and Regal, but a new 265 cu in (4.3 L) version offered 203 bhp (151 kW) and was standard equipment for the Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The *Fireball* 318 V8 engine was still an option, but only available on the Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The basic Ranger sedan featured a new low compression *Hemi-6* 215ci engine that operated on Standard grade petrol.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This engine was not available on the other sedan cars in the VH range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Unlike the VG range, Valiant Pacer was now only available in 4-door sedan form.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Apart from vivid paint colours, optional bonnet blackouts and striping, the new Pacer featured a higher performance version of the 265ci engine, with 218 bhp (163 kW) at 4,800 rpm and 273 lbf⋅ft (370 N⋅m) at 3,000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer could run the quarter-mile in 15.9 seconds, get to 100 km/h in 7.6 seconds and reach a top speed of 185 km/h.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In fact, at its release, the VH Valiant Pacer set the record for being the fastest mass-produced four-door sedan with a six-cylinder engine manufactured in Australia, a record which stood for 17 years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer's days as the VH performance model were numbered, because that same year saw the announcement and introduction of what was to become Chrysler Australia's most recognised new car – the Valiant Charger.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In total, only 1,647 VH Valiant Pacer sedans were produced.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new Valiant Charger was unlike anything that had come before and it had the Australian motoring press calling it, "...the most handsome car Chrysler has ever produced, and probably the best looking car ever produced by an Australian manufacturer".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A short-wheelbase, fastback coupe with an aggressive wedge-like stance, the Charger's design gave the effect of speed, even when it was standing still.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's TV campaign for the Charger featured the young adults at whom it was targeted, waving at one as it swept by them and shouting "Hey, Charger!" One of the more memorable TV ads of the time, it created a cliché that haunts today's owners.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Charger won *Wheels* magazine's Car of the Year award for 1971 and was widely acclaimed by others in the motoring press, as well as the public.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant Charger came in four model guises, closely mirroring the existing sedan range – Charger, Charger XL, Charger 770, and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The first of the serious "track pack" R/T Chargers had option E38.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Despite being hampered by a three-speed gearbox, it still drew favourable comments from *Wheels*: "We achieved a time of 14.8 seconds for the quarter-mile – on smoother surfaces the Charger galloped away so easily that a best of 14.5 seconds is within reach".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Being a three-speed gearbox, these quarter-mile runs took only one gear change.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The most recognised performance Chargers were the **Six Pack** cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The term *six pack* denoted the triple side-draught Weber 2BBL carburettors with which the 265 *Hemi-6* engine – in option E37, option E38, and later option E49 – produced levels of power unheard of on a naturally aspirated six-cylinder at the time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The triple carburettors also made for a distinctive throaty note when under acceleration.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] E38 versions of the Charger R/T featured a 265 *Hemi-6* which produced 280 bhp (209 kW) while the E37 was the street tune option made available on Charger 770 and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] E38 was a race-ready Charger R/T with the additional A84 Track Pack option, which included a 35-imperial-gallon (160 L) fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] There was also an A87 Track Pack option that included all the race track goodies, but for the larger fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In mid-1972, the E38 option was superseded by the more powerful and greatly refined four-speed transmission E49 option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This drew comments from *Wheels* such as, "The raw quivering power is instantaneously on tap and with a ratio for every conceivable situation the Charger just storms through.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It would take a Ferrari Daytona with racing driver Jackie Ickx at the wheel to stay with one".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] All E49s came with a Track Pack, 21 of which featured the huge fuel tank with dual fillers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The E49 six pack engine came with a baffled sump, tuned length headers, special shot-peened crankshaft, connecting rods, pistons, rings, cam, valve springs, a twin plate clutch and of course the triple 45 mm dual throat Weber carburetors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler quoted this engine as producing 302 bhp (225 kW), with the car weighing 1,372 kg (3,025 lb).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The R/T E49 was the ultimate Valiant Charger, and with only 149 built the E49s are still widely considered today as one of the greatest Australian "muscle" cars ever produced.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Road tests of the era recorded quarter-mile times of between 14.1 and 14.5 seconds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This compares to times of 14.6 for the next quickest accelerating Australian muscle car, the Ford XY Falcon GT-HO (Phase III).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although the Six Pack Chargers were the dominant performance players in the VH range, there was another Charger, the 275 bhp (205 kW), 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 powered E55, that came close.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Option E55 was applied to the new Charger 770 SE in August 1972, and this car could reach 60 mph (97 km/h) in 7.2 seconds and complete the quarter-mile in 15.5 seconds – all topped off by a top speed of 122 mph (196 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A batch of several hundred VH Charger 770 318 V8s were exported to Japan along with CH sedans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers had a CH-like nose with VH sheet metal surrounding the CH four headlights and grille, a combination that NZ assembler Todd Motors would later use to create its unique VJ Valiant Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Japanese cars also had air conditioning, side marker lights and separate white reversing lights as well as mirrors conforming to Japanese market regulations.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Overall, Chrysler Australia manufactured 67,800 VH Valiant cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand distributor Todd Motors had assembled the Valiant sedan from CKD kits since the AP5, mostly following the Australian range though with fewer variants and engine choices plus local upholstery.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Regal 770 had the 265ci *Hemi-6*, floor-console automatic shifter, round dials with wood trim in place of the strip speedo and its own unique front bucket seats and trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The 318ci V8 was optional and a vinyl roof was standard but could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Todd's sole locally built Charger model was also to '770' trim with the 265ci *Hemi-6* six and three-speed floor shift auto and did not have the bumper overriders standard in Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Early runs had one-piece front door glass and hinged opening rear side windows but, due to problems with water leaks and excessive wind noise, this was soon changed to opening front quarterlights and fixed rear side glass.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Wagons were imported from Australia, to Australian specification.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] VH Valiants were assembled at Silverton, near Pretoria in South Africa using Australian bodies, electrics and trim and locally sourced mechanical components including a 225 cid engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Prior to 1971 South African Valiants had been sourced from Canada.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VH model range also saw the introduction of the new luxury class vehicles, the **CH** range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CH was a further 4 inches (100 mm) longer in the wheelbase than the VH Valiant – 115 in (2,900 mm) – with a total length of 197 in (5,000 mm).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It featured quad round headlamps and a different rear end treatment, and had quieter suspension and higher equipment levels.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CH (or "Chrysler by Chrysler", as it is commonly referred to) was a four-door luxury model intended to compete with the Ford Fairlane and Holden's Statesman models in the luxury car market in Australia.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Also released in October 1971 was a two-door version of the CH which was called the Chrysler Hardtop, and shared the same wheelbase as the four-door Chrysler, along with the front and rear end treatment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] May 1973 saw the introduction of the next model in the new All-Australian designed Valiant – The **VJ**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although essentially a facelifted version of the VH Valiant before it, the VJ's subtle changes made enough of an impact on the buying public to make it the biggest selling Chrysler Valiant model of all, with 90,865 units being sold.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Externally the VJ Valiant continued on with the VH series body styles, though the VJ reverted to single 7" round headlamps and a new 8-segment grille.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] VJ sedans also received new horizontal taillights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although the physical changes were few, many other new features were introduced in the VJ Valiant range, such as electronic ignition, rustproofing and floor-mounted shifters as standard features.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler upgraded equipment levels in July 1974 with front disc brakes, door reflectors, lockable glovebox and retractable seatbelts all as standard features.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] While the VJ range still offered sedan, wagon, ute, hardtop and coupe variants, the performance-oriented Pacer sedans and Charger R/T coupes were deleted from the new range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] However, a variation of the E37 Six Pack engine (now with four-speed manual transmission) was made available, in the form of option E48, with most of the cars bearing this option ending up being base model VJ Charger coupes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Four VJ Charger coupes were built by special order featuring the VH series option E49 engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The other carry-over performance variant was option E55, with the 340ci V8 engine option officially remaining as restricted to Charger 770 coupe application only.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In August 1974, a special run of 500 Sportsman coupes were released, based upon the Charger XL model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] They were only available in Vintage Red with white body accents.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] These cars also had a unique white interior with plaid cloth seats and featured a standard 265 engine with a choice of either manual or automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, Todd Motors was even more adventurous with the VJ.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The base Ranger XL and Charger were updated, as in Australia, with similar NZ-only variations as the VH but the VJ Regal 770 was something of a 'parts bin special' and essentially a merger of a VJ Regal with a CH Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The nose – also used for several hundred VH Chargers built for the Japanese market – combined the CH's four headlamps and grille with VH Valiant sheetmetal (retaining the older, larger, clear park/indicator lamps) while the rest of the body was as per Australian VJ.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Inside, new front seats were CH style, with individual chairs forming a bench shape, and a column automatic shifter was now used.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Earlier cars had all-vinyl upholstery but cloth was fitted as standard later.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand VJ Regals also had a vinyl roof in black or beige and the panel between the tail lights was also trimmed in vinyl to match – the vinyl trim could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a facelift in May 1973 to become the CJ Series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The two-door hardtop was dropped leaving only the four-door sedan to carry on the fight against its Ford and Statesman luxury competitors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The related Valiant hardtop's production continued.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In October 1975 the VK Valiant was released with few external changes from the previous VJ model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger now had an argent version of the VJ Charger grille, the Charger XL had a white version and the Charger 770 also had the argent grille.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VK Valiant Regal featured a "grille within a grille".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger sedan, Regal sedan, and Charger all now shared the same tail-light treatment, using a horizontal layout with four chrome contours to keep air flow away and keep the lenses clean.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers were not called Chrysler Valiant Chargers any longer; with the 'Valiant' name being dropped.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The VK Regal also had blinker repeaters housed in small chrome boxes which sat on top of both front guards.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Another unusual option was the **Fuel Pacer** option from the Chrysler US parts bin which detected low engine vacuum – as under hard acceleration – and illuminated the driver side guardtop blinker repeater to indicate wasteful driving.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Inertia-reel seatbelts and slightly different heater controls were introduced on the VK, as well as a combination control stalk for the lights and wipers from the Mitsubishi Galant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger also got full-length door trims, and carpet was now standard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] VK six-cylinder series engines were the same as the VJ's, and the 245 *Hemi-6* now featured a two-barrel carburettor like the 265 variant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The V8s were mainly 318 cu in (5.2 L) units, though the 360 cu in (5.9 L) remained an option across the entire range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It was not very popular as the mid-1970s saw the trend towards smaller cars with smaller motors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] While the "three on the tree" column shift manual gearbox was still available, it was rarely specified (although still popular on Utes) and the three-speed floor change was now gone too.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Buyers seeking floor-shift manual could choose the four-speed, which was available on all models but could only be had with a *Hemi-6*, not with a V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Late in the VK model run a limited edition Charger called the White Knight Special (option A50) was offered with a factory-fitted front air dam.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The changes were mainly cosmetic with running gear being largely stock.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] There were 200 White Knight Specials made – 100 Arctic White and 100 Amarante Red.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] 120 were automatics and 80 were four-speeds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] 20,555 VK Valiants were produced and production ceased in June 1976.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] This was because ADR 27A for exhaust emission control became effective on 1 July 1976, and all the car manufacturers used that date as the introduction of a new model to comply with the new standard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] VK assembly did not begin in New Zealand until nearly a year after Australian launch because a 60% sales tax levied on large engine cars, introduced during the 1973-4 oil crisis, drastically slowed VJ sales.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The model range in New Zealand was pared down to Regal and Regal 770 editions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A version of the Regal was manufactured for the South African Police as the SPP package in the late 1970s which featured triple carburetors, an uprated gearbox, uprated differential, and larger disc brakes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a slight a facelift in October 1975 to become the **CK** series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Production ceased just one year later in October 1976 when the Chrysler was replaced by the Chrysler Regal SE, a prestige version of the CL Series Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL Series Valiant was introduced in November 1976.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although it used the same bodyshell as the previous VK range, the front and rear ends were restyled.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The front end used horizontally arrayed quad round headlamps flanking a central grille.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The front guards and bonnet were also reworked accordingly.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The new bootlid's curved leading edge flowed down to new taillights that sandwiched a simple centre garnish panel.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The bumpers, however, were the same units as had been used on the 1969 VF series Valiants.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger name was dropped; the base model CL was simply called *Valiant*, and the long-wheelbase "Chrysler by Chrysler" was replaced by the *Regal SE*.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL series Regal was marketed as the **Chrysler Regal**, in contrast to the Valiant Regal name used from the AP5 series through to the recently superseded VK Series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL series was the last to include a Charger model, which – like the previous VK model – was badged and sold as a *Chrysler*, not as a *Valiant* submodel.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL Charger was generally available in only one trim level, the **Charger 770**, though a **Charger XL** was made available to police departments.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL series also saw the arrival of the panel van variant to compete with similar offerings from rival makers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Interiors carried over largely unchanged from the VK range, though the Regal SE offered luxurious buttoned-leather seating as an option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Base Valiants continued with the previous Ranger style strip speedometer, while the Regal dash featured recessed circular gauges and clock with a woodgrain finish.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Charger 770 dash was similar to that of the Regal, except it was finished in black and had a tachometer instead of a clock.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The 3.5 L (215 cu in) *Hemi-6* and 5.9 L (360 cu in) V8 were dropped, and the only engine options were low- and high-compression versions of the 4.0 L (245 cu in) *Hemi-6* and the 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL's introduction had closely coincided with that of the strict exhaust emission regulations contained in ADR 27A.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] With the 318 engine, a new emissions control system was introduced: **Electronic Lean Burn**.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options were 3-speed manual with floor or column shift, four-speed manual with floor shift, and three-speed Torqueflite automatic with floor or column shift.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The automatic was standard equipment with the 318 V8, and optional with a 6-cylinder.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The 4-speed was optional for six- and eight-cylinder models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The floor-shift auto option was fitted to most Regals and all Regal SE's.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In 1978 Chrysler released a limited edition run of 400 special **Regal Le Baron** models (option A17).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Le Baron was available only in Silver, with red or blue interiors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The 265 *Hemi-6* was standard, and the 318 V8 was optional.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Regal sedans also benefited from the 1978 introduction of *Radial Tuned Suspension* in response to Holden's having marketed their suspension as particularly suited to radial tyres.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] RTS improved the car's handling and roadholding significantly, and "Modern Motor" magazine proclaimed that the Valiant offered a better drive than the Holden.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The last special option in the CL range was the $816 **Drifter** package, available on the Charger.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Drifter package included Impact Orange, Sundance Yellow, Spinnaker White or Harvest Gold body paint, and large side and rear stripes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Drifters in white had additional "strobe stripes" on the bootlid.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Engine options were again the 265 six or 318 V8, but the 4-speed manual was the only transmission option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A Drifter Pack was also offered on the Valiant Panel Van and on the Utility.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] 36,672 CL Valiants – including the last-ever Chargers – were built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CL was the last Valiant series assembled in New Zealand – by now the Chargers and Ranger were gone and the Regal and the Regal SE, replacing the 770, were the only models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The Regal SE was the first car to be assembled in the country with standard air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The CM was released in November 1978, and was little changed bodywise from the CL model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Only sedan and wagon models were produced.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A sports sedan called the GLX (option A16) was released as a replacement for the discontinued Charger and earlier the Pacer.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Its features included a Charger grill and dashboard, special cloth trim, Cheviot Hotwire mag wheels and black door frames.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] It was advertised as the car "For People Who Like Their Cars Rare", as it was the last of the sports models and the jewel in the CM series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The GLX could be optioned with a 4.3 L (265 cu in) *Hemi-6* or 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The computer-controlled Electronic Lean Burn system continued giving favourable fuel economy; when *Wheels* performed an economy test in 1979, they found the ELB-equipped Valiant 4.0 L (245 cu in) used less fuel than a 2.0 L (120 cu in) Ford Cortina.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant achieved better than 30 miles per imperial gallon (9.4 L/100 km) in the Total Oil Economy Run.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Production of this car continued after Mitsubishi's takeover of Chrysler's Australian operations.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Mitsubishi could build the car profitably even in small numbers due to its high 97% level of local Australian content and amortised tooling.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] However, the car was still badged as the *Chrysler* Valiant, not as a Mitsubishi.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The profit from the sale of one Valiant was equal to the profit from 3 Mitsubishi Sigmas- by this time the company's main seller.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Valiant production ended in August 1981 with production of the CM reaching 16,005 units out of 565,338 units of all models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Eventually, the Mitsubishi Magna was developed to replace both the Sigma and Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Full-sized Chryslers were not marketed again in Australia until the 2005 release of the Chrysler 300C.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Although the Charger is arguably the best remembered Valiant in Australian motorsport, earlier models achieved class wins at the annual "Bathurst 500" production car race, something that the Charger never did.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant AP5 won Class D at the 1963 Armstrong 500, a VC Valiant V8 won Class D at the 1966 Gallaher 500 and a VG Valiant Pacer won Class D at the 1970 Hardie-Ferodo 500.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chargers were raced in the Hardie-Ferodo 500 at Bathurst in 1971 and 1972 with factory support.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] They gained a best placing of third outright and second in class in 1972.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's policy was to race "Australian made" product, which meant the race cars ran 4.3 L (265 cu in) six-cylinder engines equipped with triple Weber carburettors and 3-speed gearboxes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] Even skilled driving and good engineering could not defeat Ford's legendary Falcon GTHO Phase III with its 351 cu in (5.75 L) V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, however, the Chryslers proved to be virtually unbeatable from 1971 to 1979 at the famous B&H 500-mile (later 1000 km) series at Pukekohe Park Raceway.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/chrysler-valiant] The most successful drivers were Leo Leonard and Jim Little, who still races his Valiants (mostly pre-65 class).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The **Dodge Lancer** is an automobile that was marketed in three unrelated versions by Dodge during the 1950s, 1960s, and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The first version debuted as a hardtop version of the full-sized 1955 Dodge, and was produced in that form until 1959.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The second version revived the nameplate in 1961 for a Chrysler A platform-based compact that was marketed for two model years and replaced by the Dodge Dart.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The third version returned the Lancer nameplate in 1985 for a front-wheel drive mid-sized Chrysler H platform model that was in production until 1988 after which it was replaced by the Dodge Spirit.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Dodge used the Lancer name from 1955 until 1959 to designate the two- and four-door hardtop (no B-pillar) models in the full-sized Coronet, Royal, and Custom Royal lines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Custom Royal Lancer was a hardtop only and top-of-the-line model for Dodge in 1959.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] There were 6,278 two-door and 5,019 four-door hardtops made in 1959.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A total of 11,397 Custom Royal Lancers were built.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Custom Royal Lancer featured a big-block V8 engine, the 361 cu in (5.9 L) producing 305 hp (227 kW; 309 PS).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A D-500 option was available, which included a 383 cu in (6.3 L) engine with a single Carter four-barrel carburetor rated at 320 hp (239 kW; 324 PS), as well as a Super D-500 version with dual four-barrel carburetors producing 340 hp (254 kW; 345 PS).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Custom Royal Lancer featured a padded dashboard and steering wheel, Lancer emblems on the fenders, steering wheel, hubcaps, foot-operated windshield wipers, dual-radio antennas, deluxe side trim, and thick chrome eyebrows.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Optional equipment included power windows and brakes, air conditioning, and swivel seats.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Lancer designation was dropped for 1960.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] For the 1961 model year, Dodge applied the Lancer nameplate to a higher-priced, upmarket badge-engineered version of Chrysler's Valiant compact.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The model was introduced when Chrysler officially assigned the Valiant to the Plymouth division for 1961, leaving Dodge dealers without a compact car to sell.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] All body styles of the Valiant were also available on the Lancer: two- and four-door sedans, two-door hardtop, and a four-door wagon.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] After 1962, the line was renamed the Dodge Dart.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A survey of 1961 Lancer owners by *Popular Mechanics* based on a total of 1,023,938-mile (1,647,868 km) miles driven reported that 77.6.2% rated their cars as excellent with handling, comfortable ride, power/performance, and styling as their top likes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Lancer wheelbase and body shell were identical to those of the Valiant, but interior and exterior trim were more upscale for the Lancer.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Lancers featured round taillights and a full-width grille, instead of the Valiant's cat's-eye taillights and central grille.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] For 1961, trim levels were the basic "170" and the premium "770".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] During 1961, the two-door hardtop was marketed as the "Lancer 770 2-Door Hardtop".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] For the 1962 model year, the hardtop was marketed as the "GT 2-Door Hardtop" and carried premium trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Two-tone paint was available and instead of the front bench seat, there were two bucket seats.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Also for the 1962 model, "Lancer GT" medallions were mounted on the doors' interior trim panels below the vent window and on the sides of the front fenders just aft of the headlamps.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] "GT" emblems were placed on the hood, the deck lid, and on the vinyl dash pad.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The headlamp bezels and the grille's horizontal slats were blacked-out.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The GT also lacked certain ornamentation found on the 170s and 770s such as the "Lancer" door scripts, the slanted chrome hash marks on the lower quarter panel, and the hook-ended stainless steel door-to-fender spears.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The base engine was the 170 cu in (2.8 L) unit, rated at 101 bhp (75 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The optional power package consisted of the larger 225 cu in (3.7 L) engine, rated at 145 bhp (108 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] After the start of the 1961 model year, a die-cast aluminum version of the 225 engine block was made available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The aluminum 225 weighed 45 lb (20 kg) less than the iron 170 and 80 lb (36 kg) less than the iron 225.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Any of the available engines could be equipped at the dealer with Chrysler's Hyper Pak parts kit for a significant power upgrade: the 170 Hyper Pak's published output was 148 bhp (110 kW), while the 225 Hyper Pak's was 196 bhp (146 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Hyper-Pak shaved more than four seconds off the 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) time versus the standard 225, and was over a second quicker and seven miles per hour faster in the quarter mile.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] With the Hyper Pak, a 225 Lancer could go from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in 8.6 seconds and turn in a standing quarter-mile time of 16.4 seconds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] 1962 cars had the engine and transmission moved for a flatter front floor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Transmission options were a Chrysler-built A903 three-speed manual with the shifter on the floor in 1961 and on the steering column in 1962, or a pushbutton-operated A904 Torqueflite three-speed automatic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] In the 1962 NHRA Winternationals, Wayne Weihe won the C/FX (Factory Experimental) class with a Hyper-Pak-equipped Lancer, clocking a 15.67 E.T.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Although the bigger Dodges were beginning to appear at drag strips around the country, the "Golden Lancer" of Dode Martin and Jim Nelson was one of the fastest compacts on the strips in 1962.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The engine was a 413 cu in (6.77 liters) Chrysler RB V8 engine modified by the Chrysler engineers' "Ramchargers" racing team.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Golden Lancer raced successfully in A/FX class and could do the quarter-mile in 12.68 seconds at 113 mph (182 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Lancer sales did not meet expectations and sold about half as well as the Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] As a late part of the total redesign of Dodge's compact car for 1963, the Lancer name was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Dodge compacts for 1963 through 1976 were named Dart, a name that had previously been assigned to a larger car produced by Dodge from 1960 through 1962.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] In South Africa, a right hand drive version of the Lancer was sold from 1961 through 1963, badged as the **DeSoto Rebel** not long after the DeSoto name was discontinued in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] All were equipped with the 170 cu in (2.8 L) Slant 6 engine, and most had the three-speed manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] As with the Australian RV1 and SV1 Valiants, the DeSoto Rebel used the instrument cluster from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] White reflectors were mounted to the front bumper, in compliance with South African vehicle equipment regulations.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Rebel name was re-introduced by Chrysler South Africa in 1967 as the economy-priced "Valiant Rebel".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Dodge Lancer was re-introduced in 1985 as a mid-sized 5-door hatchback.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] It was a rebadged version of the Chrysler LeBaron GTS and was based on the Chrysler H platform, a stretched version of the Chrysler K platform.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Lancer eventually slotted between the Aries and the 600.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] All Lancers were built in Sterling Heights, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Production ended on April 7, 1989, and the market position was replaced by the Spirit.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A special version was available for the 1987 model year called the Shelby Lancer, which was built by Shelby Automobiles in Whittier, California.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A total of 800 units were produced with half featuring a 5-speed manual transmission and cloth seats while the other half were equipped with a 3-speed automatic transmission and leather upholstery.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Along with Shelby-themed trim changes, the cars included modified suspension, with upgraded sway bars, shorter springs, and quicker steering, as well as 4-wheel disc brakes and a Pioneer CD player which were an advanced features for the time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Lancer Shelby is powered by a 2.2 L Turbo I engine converted to Turbo II specifications with an intercooler, producing 175 hp (130 kW) and 175 lb⋅ft (237 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Period 0-60 mph (97 km/h) tests achieved between 7.2 and 8.0 seconds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Chrysler took over production starting with the 1988 model year, building them in the same Sterling Heights plant as regular Lancers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The "Dodge Lancer Shelby" featured many of the same appearance and handling modifications as the Shelby, with some omissions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] These included the upgraded sway bars, shorter springs, and quicker steering along with other comfort and convenience features such as leather seats, power locks, windows, seats and mirrors, a tilt steering wheel, and a two-position cup holder.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] While some of the modifications from the 1987 Shelbys were included, the Shelby shocks and wheels were replaced by Chrysler units and the rear disk brakes were discontinued in favor of the regular Lancer's rear drums.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Most of the Shelby graphics and badges were also removed and the Pioneer CD player was replaced by Chrysler's Infinity II system.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] While the 1987 models were only available in red, the 1988 and 1989 models added a choice of white or black.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Lancer Shelby used a true intercooled Turbo II engine for the manual transmission version, providing the same 175 hp (130 kW) and 175 lb⋅ft (237 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The automatic variant was equipped with the 146 hp (109 kW) Turbo I.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] 279 Lancer Shelbys were produced in 1988 and 208 in 1989 for a total of 487 units.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] In April 1988, Chrysler started offering some models on the European market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] One of them was the "Chrysler GTS", a rebadged version of the Dodge Lancer ES.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Due to European vehicle regulations, the exterior appearance was slightly different.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The rear turn signals were amber rather than red, the front sidemarkers and the centre high mount stop lamp (CHMSL) were blanked off, small round repeaters were installed into the front fenders and the sideview mirrors were of spring-hinged rather than rigid design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The engine options included the naturally aspirated 2.2 L (134 cu in) Four, and a turbocharged version of the same engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] From 1989 on, the 2.5 L (153 cu in) Four became available with or without a turbocharger.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The 2.2 engine was dropped, except for the Turbo II version that was standard equipment on the Chrysler GTS Shelby, the European sibling of the Dodge Lancer Shelby.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] A five-speed manual gearbox was standard, with a three-speed automatic transmission as an extra-cost option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The GTS Shelby came only with a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] The Chrysler GTS had few buyers in Europe; the competition was too hard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] Even the comparatively low prices could not help, and sales figures were very low.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/desoto-rebel] By the end of 1989, the GTS was replaced by the Saratoga.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The **Dodge Dart** is a line of passenger cars produced by Dodge from the 1959 to 1976 model years in North America, with production extended to later years in various other markets.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The production Dodge Dart was introduced as a lower-priced full-size model in 1960 and 1961, but became a mid-size car for one model year for 1962, and was then reduced to a compact for two generations, from 1963 to 1976.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler had first used 'Dart' name plates on two Italian styled show cars, in 1956 and 1957, before it became a Dodge model name.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart nameplate was resurrected for a Fiat-derived compact car that was introduced in 2012.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart name originally appeared on a 1956 Chrysler show car, featuring a streamlined body designed by the Italian coachbuilder Carrozzeria Ghia, that was later modified and renamed the Dart Diablo.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For 1957, Ghia built Chrysler a second, visually similar show car, the Chrysler Ghia Super Dart 400.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The first Dodge Darts were introduced for the 1960 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] They were downsized large cars developed to replace Plymouths in the standard, low-priced car segment for the Dodge dealer network.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge dealers had been selling Plymouths since 1930, but divisional restructuring took the Plymouth brand away from the Dodge dealer network.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Project planners proposed the name Dart, only to have Chrysler executives demand an expensive research program that produced the name Zipp.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] This was promptly rejected in favor of Dart.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] With the cancellation of Chrysler's upper level DeSoto brand, upper-level Dodge products were pushed upmarket, while using Plymouth products with more features for lower-level Dodge products.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart sedans and coupes were based on the unibody Plymouth platform with a 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase, shorter than the standard-size Dodge line.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] However, the Dart station wagons used the same 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase as the upmarket Polara wagons.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart line was offered in three trim levels: the basic Seneca, mid-range Pioneer, and premium Phoenix.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The new Dart came standard with a new engine, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-six.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 318 cu in (5.2 L) (standard equipment on certain Phoenix and Pioneer body styles) and 361 cu in (5.9 L) V8s were optional with two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, and with single or dual exhaust.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Sales of the new Dart were greater than those of the full-size Dodge Matador and Dodge Polara, which also created an in-house competitor for Plymouth.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Advertising from 1960 and 1961 compared the Dart to the "C" car (Chevrolet), the "F" car (Ford) and the "P" car (Plymouth).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] After the economic downturn of 1958–59, Dodge production for 1960 rebounded to 367,804 cars, the division's highest total to date, and good for sixth place behind Chevrolet, Ford, Plymouth, Rambler, and Pontiac.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler officials were somewhat less comforted at how 87% of Dodge's volume consisted of the low-profit Dart line, compared to the upmarket Matador and Polara, of which only 41,000 were sold for the 1960 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] As the Dart's sales climbed, Plymouth's sales dropped.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler executives did little to stop the infighting between the divisions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dart sales were so strong in 1960 that production of the medium-priced model lines were reduced.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The full-size, mid-priced Matador was discontinued after the 1960 model year as buyers selected the slightly smaller but better-appointed and less expensive Dart Phoenix.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The premium Polara remained in the medium-price segment in 1961.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For the 1961 model year, the Dart continued as the smallest full-size Dodge.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It retained the 118 in (2,997 mm) wheelbase, and was restyled to emulate the larger Polara.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The same three trim levels were available: the premium Phoenix, mid-range Pioneer, and base Seneca.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Once again, wagons shared the Polara's 122 in (3,099 mm) wheelbase; they also shared the Polara's unique side-mounted taillights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Engine choices included the 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-six, and the 318 cu in (5.2 L) and 361 cu in (5.9 L) V8s were also available in various configurations.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Phoenix convertibles were equipped with V8 engines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Beginning mid-year, some Darts ordered with the 225 engine were equipped with the die-cast aluminum block.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Darts in all series were equipped as standard with three-speed, column-shifted manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's pushbutton-shifted TorqueFlite automatic was available at extra cost.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The alternator, introduced as standard equipment in 1960 on the Valiant, replaced the previous DC generator on all 1961 Chrysler products.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Canadian-built 1961 Darts were identical to U.S. models on the outside, but the interior trim, controls, and displays were those used on the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Virgil Exner's 1961 styling with its reverse fins, rear fender scalloping (the taillights were widely referred to as "ingrown toenails"), and the concave grille was highly unpopular with consumers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The low position and small size of the Dart's tail lights, just above the corners of the bumper, was also criticized and drivers of following cars complained that they could not see them.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The wraparound taillights projected light sideward, not rearward.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] By mid-year, Dodge made auxiliary taillights available at extra cost through its dealer network.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] However, these large round lights were mounted near the inboard side of the reverse fins and aggravated the already awkward styling.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1961 automobile market was generally an off-year for automobile sales, and Dodge production went down to 269,367 units, of which 142,708 were Darts.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Among all the Darts sold, almost half (66,100) were the Seneca line, down from 111,600 in 1960.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Combined sales of Dart and Polara were lower than Plymouth's sales for 1961.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge ranked ninth in sales in the American market in 1961, down from sixth place in 1960.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Sales of the compact Dodge Lancer were 74,773 units compared to its Plymouth twin, the Valiant, which sold 143,078 units for the same year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1961 model year saw Dodge's total production drop below the slow-selling 1959 model year and almost the disastrous recession year of 1958 when Dodge faced the consequences of the poor reputation of its 1957 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dodge Polara 500 was dimensionally identical but not officially a Dart by dint of its different name, and it was not built nor sold in Canada.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart models were the same in Canada as in the U.S. except that the base model was badged *Dart 220*.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart and Polara were downsized as part of Chrysler's hasty effort to compete with what company leaders thought would be downsized large cars from Chevrolet.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] However, they had overheard talk not of the big Chevrolets, but of the compact Chevy II Nova.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] This was a basic front-engine compact to compete more directly than the Corvair with the Ford Falcon, Rambler American, and Plymouth Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chevrolet's Impala and Ford's Galaxie both remained sized in accord with the prevailing norms of full-size cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The redesigned Dart was perceived more as an intermediate, like the Rambler Classic or the Ford Fairlane.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] When Dodge dealers voiced their displeasure at having no true full-size car to offer, Chrysler quickly created the Dodge Custom 880 in January 1962 by putting the 1961 Dodge Polara front end assembly on a version of the 1962 Chrysler Newport body.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1962 Dart, like the Plymouth, was on a new lightweight unibody "B" platform, featuring Chrysler's well-received "Torsion-Aire" torsion bar front suspension and asymmetric rear leaf springs.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1961, a third-generation turbine engine (CR2A) was installed in a 1962 Dart, which successfully drove from New York City to Los Angeles, through snowstorms, rain and heavy winds.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart's new B-body chassis platform was quite long-lived; while 1962 was the only year for a B-body model named "Dart", the B platform remained in use with only very slight modification and a few new letter designations through to the 1981 R-body cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For 1963, Dodge made a last-minute decision to drop the Lancer name in favor of *Dart* for Dodge's newly designed "senior compact", a marketing term referring to the wheelbase having grown to 111 in (2,819 mm) from the Lancer's 106.5 in (2,705 mm).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The longer wheelbase gave more rear seat legroom than the previous Lancer or the contemporaneous Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was available as a 2- or 4-door sedan, a 2-door hardtop coupe, a station wagon, and a convertible.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Three trim levels were offered: the low-spec *170*, the high-spec *270*, and the premium *GT*, which was available only as a 2-door hardtop or convertible.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1963 Dart has a turning diameter of 38.9 ft (11.9 m).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was an instant market success, with 1963 sales up sharply compared to those of the 1962 Lancer.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart remained extremely popular through the end of the Dart's production run in 1976 in comparison to the Ford Falcon and the Chevrolet Nova.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Initial engine offerings were two sizes of the slant-six: a 170 cu in (2.8 L), 101 hp (75 kW) version was fitted as standard equipment, and a 225 cu in (3.7 L), 145 hp (108 kW) version was available for less than $50 extra.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The aluminum engine block for the 225 was discontinued early in the 1963 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] After the start of the 1964 model year, an all-new, compact, lightweight 273 cu in (4.5 L) LA V8 producing 180 bhp (130 kW) with a 2-barrel carburetor was introduced as the top engine option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] 1964 was the last year for pushbutton control of the optional Torqueflite automatic transmission, so 1963 and 1964 models were the only compact Darts so equipped.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Standard axle ratios in 1964 were 2.93:1 with automatic transmission and 225 engine, or 3.23:1 with manual transmission and 225 engine, or with 170 engine and either transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] New features included stronger door locks and a refined automatic choke.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1965, the 2-barrel 273 remained available, but a new performance version of the 273 engine was released with a 4-barrel carburetor, 10.5:1 compression, a more aggressive camshaft with solid tappets, and other upgrades which increased output to 235 bhp (175 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] At the same time, the Dodge Dart Charger was offered.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Chargers were yellow Dart GT hardtops with black interiors, Charger 273 engines, (Plymouth called their 4 barrel 273 Commando), premium mechanical and trim specifications, and special "Charger" badging.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] They were the first Dodge models to bear the "Charger" name.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The following year the larger B-body Dodge Charger was introduced, and the "Charger" name was thenceforth associated with Dart models only in the "Charger 225" marketing name for the optional larger 6-cylinder engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Other new options for 1965 included upgraded suspension components and larger 14 in (356 mm) wheels and tires.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Factory-installed air conditioning became available after the start of the 1965 model year, as well as disc brakes, which required the 14 in (356 mm) wheels to clear the calipers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For North American domestic-market vehicles, the base 170 engine was replaced for 1970 with a stronger new 198 cu in (3.2 L) version of the slant-6.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] This new base engine was also less costly to make, for unlike the previous 170 engine, the 198 used the same block as the 225.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The smaller displacement was achieved with a new crankshaft (3.64 in (92 mm) stroke vs. the 4.125 in (104.8 mm) stroke of the 225 crank) and connecting rods (7.006 in (178.0 mm) long vs. the 6.67 in (169 mm) rods in the 225).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Nevertheless, the 225 remained an upgrade option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 2-barrel 273 cu in (4.5 L) small-block V8 was supplanted on the option list in 1968 by a 318 cu in (5.2 L) 2-barrel engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] At the same time the 4-barrel carbureted 273 235 bhp (175 kW) was replaced on the options list by the 275 bhp (205 kW) 4-barrel carbureted 340 cu in (5.6 L) available only in the 1968–1972 Swinger and the hottest Dart, the performance-oriented GTS models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart GTS came standard with the 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart and its sister model—the Plymouth Valiant—were substantially redesigned for the 1967 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In addition to new styling, the cars received revised steering systems, wider front track and frame rail spacing, and redesigned K-members capable of accepting larger engines.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart kept this basic form, with facelifts consisting of revised front and rear-end styling and interior trim, until the end of A-body production in 1976 for North America and 1981 for South America.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The restyled Dart for 1967 featured a rear window with compound inverse curves.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] This created a unique appearance at the rear of the greenhouse, but tended to collect snow and created thick C-pillars that looked formal but created blind spots for drivers.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Curved side glass was used for the first time on a Chrysler compact.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The front featured a new dual-plane front end contour: the center section of the grille, bumper, and leading edge of the hood were recessed from the front plane of the car.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The single headlamps were placed forward of the recessed center section, defining the front plane.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Park/turn lamps were set into the grille, in the corners formed by the transition area between the recessed and forward sections.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] With the new design, changes were made to the Dart lineup, beginning with the elimination of its station wagons and the base model's "170" designation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The only body styles were the 2- and 4-door sedans, the hardtop, and the convertible.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The base 170 model was now badged simply as "Dart".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 270 and GT versions carried on unchanged for the most part.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In late 1967, the GTS model debuted but was built in limited quantities due to its lateness in the model year; the 1968 GTS was, arguably, improved by fitting the new high-output 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1967 Dart, along with all other 1967 Chrysler products, got a new dual-circuit brake hydraulic system to ensure a loss of pressure in the front brakes would not prevent the rear brakes from working, and vice versa.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The system also incorporated a brake system fault telltale on the dashboard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Other changes to comply with new federal safety laws included collapsible steering columns, additional padding on the dashboard and sun visors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder belt anchors were also provided for front outboard occupants.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1967 redesign removed all traces of the older Virgil Exner styling that proved less popular by the early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The newer body was trimmer and proved extremely popular, causing sales of the Dart to surpass compacts from Ford and GM.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Changes for 1968 were relatively subtle.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The park and turn lights in the grille were moved slightly inboard and made round.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Side marker lights were added to the front fenders and rear quarter panels, to comply with newly introduced Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 108.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder harnesses (separate, this year and until 1973, from the lap belts) and non-glare matte finish on the windshield wiper arms were also part of the 1968 federally mandated safety package.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's "clean air package" emission control system became standard equipment on cars sold in all 50 states.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The steering linkage was revised again, as were the windshield and rear window gaskets and trim-lock strips, leaving the 1967 pieces as one-year-only items.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The standard rear axle ratio was dropped from 2.93 to 2.76 with all standard-performance engines and automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Part-throttle downshift functionality was added as a refinement to the TorqueFlite automatic transmission in 6-cylinder cars, to retain acceptable city performance with the taller rear axle ratio.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A limited option for 1968 only, code L023, the Hurst-reworked Hemi Darts used the 426 cu in (7.0 L) Hemi engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] These special models (only 80 were made) were created strictly for drag racing, and included a non-warranty disclaimer.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] On February 20, 1968, corporate headquarters in Highland Park, Michigan, sent out a press release to Dodge dealerships.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was a promotional pitch purposed at selling drag-ready, Hemi-powered Darts.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The press release stated that Dodge wanted to make a factory-built and ready drag racer out of the 68 Dart GTS hardtop for competition in class B Super Stock (drag racing).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Engineers stated the new Hemi Dart reached speeds of 130 mph (209 km/h) in less than 11 seconds and 1⁄4 mi (402 m) times in the 10-11 second range, although times have been reported as low as the 9-10 second range.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] To keep weight low, a fiberglass hood and fenders were used.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The hood featured a functional intake scoop and four hood pins for full lift-off removal of the hood.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Lightweight acid-dipped steel doors with thin side window glass were used.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] As the doors lacked a window mechanism, a strap was attached to the bottom of the glass on the interior door panel.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] To keep glass up, the strap latched to the inside of the door.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The interior included only two bucket seats from a Dodge van.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The center console, heater, sound deadeners, side-view mirrors, radio, carpeting, and even armrests were omitted to save weight.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A high-performance Mopar battery was moved to the trunk to free up room and improve weight distribution.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Darts could be ordered with either a four-speed manual or three-speed automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Manual transmission equipped cars, code A-833, featured a Dana 60 built heavy-duty axle with a 4.88 gear ratio, heavy-duty clutch, steel bellhousing, and special torque shaft and pivots.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Manual transmissions were modified by removing synchronizers which lowered the chances of missed shifts.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A Hurst floor-mounted shifter came standard.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The automatic transmissions were the then-new Chrysler-built 727 TorqueFlite three-speed with 8-3/4 inch large stem pinion center section with a 4.86 gear set, and a 2,600 rpm high speed torque converter.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] They were also modified with a floor-mounted Hurst shifter for manual shifting.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Other features include heavy-duty rear shocks, heavy-duty radiator with a seven-blade fan, and deep groove pulleys, a high capacity oil pump, solid-lifter cam, and a roller timing chain to reduce stretch and provide more reliable performance.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A transistorized dual points breaker distributor coupled with a Prestolite ignition and solid core wires were also used.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The cars weighed approximately 3,000 lb (1,361 kg).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The cars were designed to meet street legal requirements, but due to the modifications, the cars came with disclaimers that they were not for street use, but rather "supervised acceleration trials", or drag racing.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 2-door sedan was dropped at the end of 1968 and replaced with the Swinger 2-door hardtop for 1969 available in Custom, GT, and GTS trim.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The entire 1969 Dart range received trim updates including another minor revision of the grille and a return to rectangular park/turn lights.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1968 round side marker lights were replaced with rectangular reflectors.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Head restraints were optional equipment until January 1, 1969, when their installation became mandatory under federal law.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 6-cylinder models received a carburetor anti-ice system borrowed from Canadian-market Chrysler 6-cylinder engines, and the drum brake automatic adjusters were revised for more consistent operation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] At the top of the Dart performance range for 1969, there was limited availability of the 440 V8 in the Dart GTS model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart was refreshed for 1970 with front and rear changes designed to bring the car closer to the design themes found in Dodge's full-size vehicles through grille and contour changes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In the rear, the Dart's new rectangular tail lights were set into a wedge-shaped rear bumper design continuing the angled trailing edge of the new deck lid and quarter panels.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The revised rear styling did not change the 14.1 cubic ft trunk space of the 1969 model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] 14-inch wheels became standard equipment, and the 170 cu in (2.8 L) slant-6 was replaced by a larger 198 cu in (3.2 L) version for improved base-model performance and greater manufacturing economy—the 198 used the same block as the 225, while the 170 had used a different block.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Changes to the fuel system improved drivability, economy, and emission control.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Part-throttle downshift was added to the 8-cylinder automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In compliance with FMVSS 108, side marker lights and reflectors were installed at all four corners.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] 1970 Darts for the US and Canadian markets were built in Canada at the Windsor, Ontario, or Los Angeles, California assembly plant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] All 1970 Darts got the federally mandated steering column and ignition lock.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The "Swinger" name was applied to all the Dart two-door hardtops except in the high-line custom series.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Other changes were made to the Dart line to avoid internal competition with Dodge's new Challenger: the Dart convertible was discontinued along with the optional 383 cu in (6.3 L) V8, leaving the 275 bhp (205 kW) 340 4-barrel V8 as the top Dart engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The performance model in the Dart line for 1970 was the Swinger 340 2-door hardtop.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1970 Swinger 340 came with functional hood scoops with 340 emblems.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Standard equipment included front disc brakes (only on the Swinger), heavy-duty "Rallye" suspension, a 3.23:1 rear axle ratio, fiberglass-belted bias-ply tires mounted to 14 × 5½ inch steel wheels, and a bumblebee stripe.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Optional equipment included an upgrade over the standard bench seat with all-vinyl bucket seats, with which a center console could be ordered.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A performance hood upgrade with scoops was painted flat black with hood tie-down pins.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Mechanical options included power-assisted brakes and steering.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Rallye wheels and wire wheel covers were also optional, as was a 6000 rpm tachometer and a vinyl roof covering in black or white.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For 1971, Chrysler introduced a 2-door hardtop in the Valiant line called the Scamp.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was the same car as the Swinger with a Valiant front clip.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1970 Dart's dual tail lamps were given over to the badge-engineered Scamp, while the 1971 Dart received new smaller quad taillamps that would be used through 1973.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The custom 2-door hardtop coupe became the Swinger, and the standard Swinger became the Swinger Special.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge gained a version of Plymouth's popular Valiant-based fastback Duster which was to be named the *Beaver*, but when Chrysler's marketing department learned that "beaver" was CB slang for vagina, the vehicle was renamed the "Dart Demon".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] As was the case with previous Dodge rebadges of Plymouth Valiants, such as the 1961–1962 Lancer, sales of the Demon lagged behind those of the Duster.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] With optional hood scoops and blackout hood treatment, the car was advertised as a performance car.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon's Dart-type front fender wheel lips and Duster-type rear wheel fender lips reveal the car was essentially a Duster with Dart front sheet metal and other minor styling changes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A new audio option became available for 1971: Chrysler's cassette-recorder.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Unlike the 8-track tapes, the cassette player was relatively compact, and it was mounted on the console or on its own floor-mount casing.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] This unit offered an available microphone in which one could record their own dictation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Swinger 340, Dart's performance model, was replaced by the Demon 340, 275 HP engine with an optional 4-speed manual transmission, optional hood scoops, and blackout hood treatment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1971, Chrysler ended their longstanding corporate practice of installing left-hand-threaded wheel studs on the left side of the vehicle; all-wheel studs on the Dart thenceforth used conventional right-hand threads.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon had new fender-mounted metal "Demon" badges without the small devil character on the 1971 decals.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The "Demon" decal on the rear of the car was replaced by *Dodge* and *Dart* emblems on the lower right edge of the deck lid.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Some Demons with the side and rear panel tape stripes retained the tape devil character.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A new, optional, single, hood scoop replaced 1971's dual scoops, and was coupled with a hood-paint blackout that had been standard on the 1971 high-trim/high-value Demon Sizzler model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Cars equipped with the optional rally wheels now came with newly restyled center caps, finished in a light-argent (silver) paint.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Demon production was substantially less than the Duster's; this is reflected in higher collector car values for the Demon, especially V8 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1973 model year Darts received new front styling with revised fenders, grille, header panel, and hood.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Impact absorbing front bumpers were installed to comply with new federal regulations, as well as side-impact guard beams in the doors and new emission control devices.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] New single-piston disc brakes replaced the more complex 4-piston units offered from 1965 to 1972.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Chrysler's new electronic ignition system was standard equipment on all engines, and starter motors were revised for faster engine cranking.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The K-frame was modified to accommodate a new spool-type engine mount that limited engine roll to 3°.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The upper ball joints were upgraded to the larger B-body units.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Along with these chassis changes, the wheel bolt pattern on Darts with disc brakes was enlarged from 4 in (101.6 mm) to the 4.5 in (114.3 mm) pattern common to the larger B- and C-body Chrysler-built passenger cars.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Darts with 4-wheel drum brakes continued with the smaller bolt pattern.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The standard rear axle was still the 7¼-inch unit, but the heavy-duty option was now an 8¼-inch item rather than the previous 8¾-inch rear axle.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Standard rear axle ratios were 2.76:1 with automatic transmission and 3.23:1 with manual, though other ratios were available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Vent wings were deleted from the Swinger but not from the 4-door sedans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A new "Quiet Car" package was available, consisting of extra sound insulation, premium exhaust hangers, and an exhaust resonator.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Demon fastback was renamed "Dart Sport" in response to poor sales.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was thought that the "Demon" name and devil-with-pitchfork logo negatively affected sales to people of faith.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The high-performance model thus became Dart Sport 340, and 1973 saw styling changes to go along with the name change.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport received the same new front end as the other Darts, and its taillights were changed to two lights per side, each with a chrome trim ring.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] These would remain unchanged through the 1976 model year.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1974, the US federal 5 mph (8.0 km/h) bumper impact standards were expanded to cover rear bumpers as well as front ones, and as a result, the Swinger and Dart sedan's rear bumpers grew much more massive.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Taillights larger than the previous year's items were set above the rear bumper, rather than within it.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Shoulder and lap belts were finally combined in all Chrysler products into a retractable, inertia-sensitive, single-buckle design Chrysler called "Unibelt", replacing the difficult-to-use separate lap and shoulder belts that had been installed through 1973.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Arab oil embargo of 1973, increased sales of smaller cars in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge introduced the Dart SE (special edition) in mid-1974 as a four-door sedan and two-door hardtop.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The SE included velour high back bucket seats with folding armrest, carpeted door panels, woodgrain instrument panel, and deluxe wheel covers along with a TorqueFlite automatic transmission as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The SE came equipped with the "quiet car" package introduced in 1973.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The air conditioning system available on all Darts had increased capacity, quicker cooldown and lower minimum temperatures.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] An evaporator pressure regulator valve, long used on larger Chrysler products, varied the compressor's capacity without cycling the clutch.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport 340 was replaced by the Dart Sport 360 245 Bhp. as the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engine replaced the 340 cu in (5.6 L) engine discontinued after 1973.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 1975 models were virtually identical to the 1974s, except for a new grille and that California and some high-altitude models were equipped with catalytic converters and so required unleaded gasoline.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] All 1975 models were required to pass a roof crush test and to meet this stringent requirement, additional reinforcements were added to all Dart 2-door hardtops.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Heavy gauge steel in the windshield pillar area had been incorporated into the windshield, pillar, and roof design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Darts were also equipped with an improved energy-absorbing steering column which used multiple slots in the column jacket to replace prior used convoluted mesh design.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] At impact, force applied to the steering wheel curled the column jacket back over a mandrel mounted on the floor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Federal Motor Safety Standards briefly required that the front seat belts include a starter interlock system that prevented the engine from starting unless the front seat outboard occupant and the driver fastened their belts.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 198 slant-six engine was discontinued and the 225 became standard equipment on all models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] As in 1974, the 360 V8 was limited to the Dart Sport 360 model.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A 4-speed manual transmission was offered with the 6-cylinder engine for the first time in the North American market since 1965 and with a new 30% overdrive 4th gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was Chrysler's first application of overdrive since 1959.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The final drive ratio in fourth gear was 2.36:1 on the slant-six cars equipped with 3.23:1 rear axle, and 2.15:1 on the V8s equipped with 2.94:1 rear axle.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The result was less engine noise and wear and greater fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Also for 1975, heaters had 14% more heating capacity than in the previous year's models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The added capacity was the result of adding a third speed to the blower system, which provided 20% greater airflow at maximum setting.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The electrically heated backglass defogger grid timer cycle was doubled to 10 minutes.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Additionally, sound insulation was improved.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] 1976 was the Dart's final year in the North-American market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The rear-view mirror was mounted on the windshield rather than from the roof.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The grille's parking lamps were cast in amber, whereas the previous years had clear lenses with amber-colored bulbs.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Sport 360 was dropped as a separate model in 1976, but the 360 cu in (5.9 L) four-barrel, dual exhaust (without catalytic converters) V8 was a $376 option (except in California) for the $3,370 Dart Sport V8 models with automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] *Car & Driver* magazine tested the Dart Sport 360 in the April 1976 issue, pitting it against the Chevrolet Corvette and Pontiac Trans Am, and found its top speed of 121.6 mph (195.7 km/h) to be second to the Corvette's 124.5 mph (200.4 km/h).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dart Custom 4-Door Sedan was dropped as the mid-level 4-door sedan model, but the features and trim were carried over as option package A68.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Sedans equipped with the Custom package received the same "Custom" front fender badges as were applied to the standalone 1975 models of the same name.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Elimination of the Custom series narrowed Dart's 4-Door Sedan offerings in Dart's final year to two models, Dart and Dart Special Edition.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1976, the Dart was offered with a police package, with production code A38.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The A38 Dart had high-specification components and systems throughout, including a heavy-duty suspension with a rear sway bar, stronger leaf springs and firmer shock absorbers, larger brakes with semi-metallic front disc pads, maximum engine cooling as well as a high-capacity alternator and battery.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The engines were Chrysler's 225 slant-six, 318 V8, and 360 cu in (5.9 L) LA V8 (220 H.P., with non-catalyst in 49-state models and a true dual exhaust; California models had a single exhaust with the catalytic converter) with an A727 TorqueFlite transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Police-specific equipment such as a calibrated speedometer ("certified" 120 mph), high-intensity dome light and wiring harness for a rooftop light bar were standard equipment with an A-pillar spotlight and push bars were optional.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Production volume was low, with most A38 Darts going to the Los Angeles and Ventura police departments in Southern California.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For the most part, police agencies preferred the larger intermediate Dodge Coronet or full-size Dodge Monaco.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] For 1973 and 1974, the **Convertriple** option on the Dart Sport included a fold-down rear seat/security panel offering 6 ft 5 in (1.96 m) of lengthwise space, and a manually operated metal sunroof.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was advertised as "three cars in one": an economy compact, a convertible alternative because of the sunroof, and a roomy station wagon alternative because of the fold down rear seat.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Convertriple was the basis for the 1975 **Hang 10** option.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] It was aimed at surfers in an attempt by Dodge marketers to better determine consumer preferences in a declining performance market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Hang ten is a surfing expression for balancing at the end of a surfboard with ten toes over the nose of the board while riding the wave.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Available only in eggshell white exterior with a factory-installed sunroof, the car's fold-down rear seat permitted the loading of a surfboard through the trunk.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Hang 10 option continued the surfing theme with various colored stripe material accenting the white vinyl seats and door panels.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Orange shag carpet covered the back of the fold-down rear seat while the dash and center console had orange accents.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Red and blue exterior stripes started at the quarter panels with a wave-riding surfer graphic.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] A surfboard design ran down the center of the hood.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In mid-1974, Dodge introduced the **Caravan Tan** trim package.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Features for this Dart Sport included a desert-hued vinyl bench seat with multi-colored striped inserts and white piping, and gold-colored instrument panel, dashboard, and carpeting.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Exterior color choices were dark moonstone, Sienna, gold metallic, dark gold metallic, golden fawn, and white.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In a tie-in with the United States Bicentennial, a **Spirit of '76** edition of the Dart Sport featured white paint with prominent red and blue bodyside striping meant to evoke the image of the American flag.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In response to increased interest in fuel economy, Dodge offered the **Dart Lite** fuel economy package which weighed at least 150 lb (68 kg) less than the ordinary Dart Sport.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The 225 slant-six was the only available engine, equipped with an aluminum intake manifold for the first time since 1960 and a specially calibrated carburetor and distributor.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Bumper reinforcement brackets were aluminum instead of steel, while the hood and trunk lid bracing and inner panels were also aluminum.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The slant-six engine block had already been modified for reduced weight in 1975; in the middle of 1976 production, its crankshaft was changed from forged steel to lighter cast iron.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The high-flow exhaust system included a dual-biscuit catalytic converter, a larger 2¼" headpipe, and the muffler used on V8 models.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Lite was equipped with a 2.94:1 rear axle rather than the customary 3.21:1 ratio when the car was ordered with a three- or four-speed manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The A833OD Overdrive 4-speed manual transmission housing was made of aluminum and had a .73:1 final drive ratio which allowed cruising at highway speeds with minimum engine revolutions.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Like all other Darts, the Dart Lites with automatic transmission came with a 2.76:1 rear axle as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The Dart Lite with manual transmission was rated by the EPA at 36 mpg (6.5 L/100km) in highway driving.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Darts were offered to the taxicab industry for their whole production run from 1963 to 1976.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Mechanically, Dart taxicabs were generally equipped with heavy-duty brakes, tires, shock absorbers, front torsion bars and rear leaf springs, a high-output alternator, an increased-capacity cooling system, and extra-lean carburetor calibration for greater economy.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1976, the Chrome Yellow taxi package was available only with a 225 slant-six engine producing 95 hp (71 kW) and 170 lb⋅ft (230 N⋅m); transmission was the (rare) A-727-RG (raised-deck motor, which was the slant-six series) with California emissions, 90 hp (67 kW) and 165 lb⋅ft (224 N⋅m).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Options included a radio suppression package and a Fuel Pacer System.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Many—if not all—of them had a body-color paint sales code of "999", meaning special order paint.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge offered a performance version of the Dart GT in 1966.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Known as the D-Dart for competitive use in NHRA's D/stock class, the 273 V8 was modified to produce 275 bhp (205 kW).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Most of the power came from a larger carburetor and a more radical camshaft.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The bulletin sent to the dealers from Chrysler also mentions an 8.75 in (222 mm) rear axle with 4.89:1 final drive ratio.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1966, the SCCA introduced the new Trans-American Sedan Championship that allowed competition among Dodge Darts, Plymouth Barracudas, Chevrolet Corvairs, Ford Mustangs, and other "production touring cars" with a maximum wheelbase of 116 in (2,946.4 mm).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The cars competed in two classes, over 2 liters and under 2 liters.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Few modifications were allowed; bumpers, rear seats, and floor mats could be removed, mufflers could be replaced with straight pipes, and different wheels could be used so long as the stock rim diameter and width were maintained.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Any engine component available over the dealer parts counter was sanctioned for use.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Bob Tullius' race team, called "Group 44," used Dart 270 model coupes and GT coupes with 273-4bbl engines and were sponsored by Quaker State.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] The team won the 24-hour endurance race at Marlboro Motor Raceway in car No.4 driven by Tullius and Tony Adamowicz, who would also go on to win at Riverside International Raceway.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Dodge pulled sponsorship of the Darts after one season.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] Although racers like Dick Landy and Don Garlits had modified Darts in the mid-1960s to run in the National Hot Rod Association - NHRA funny car class using the 426 Hemi, super stock class racing of the Dart was almost non-existent due to the small V-8s available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] In 1968, Dodge contracted Hurst Performance to build a limited number of Darts powered by the 440 cu in (7.2 L) RB big-block and 426 cu in (7.0 L) Hemi-powered Darts to compete in the SS/B class as the LO23 "Hurst Hemi Dart".
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p01] According to Chrysler staff engineer Larry Shepard, the majority of these Darts were Hemi powered, although a small pilot run of fifty 440-powered Darts were also built in 1968.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Right-hand drive 1960, 1961, and 1962 Darts were exported to Commonwealth countries such as Australia, New Zealand, South Africa, and Singapore.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] In Australia they were badged as the Dodge Phoenix.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] In South Africa, a DeSoto-branded version of the car called the Diplomat was sold from 1960 to 1962, as well.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Once the "Dart" name was moved to Dodge's compact car for 1963, the Phoenix was no longer Dart-related; each year thereafter through 1971, the "Phoenix" name was applied to the RHD version of a Dodge or Plymouth B-body or C-body for Commonwealth export.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Chrysler Australia used the 1967 Dart front end in the Australian-built VE Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The two-door coupe versions of the subsequent VF and VG models used the Dart two-door's body from the A-pillar back married to an Australian front end.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Australian sedan and pickup truck models were also exported in knock-down kit form to New Zealand for local assembly there from 1963 to 1978.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Dodge Darts were assembled in right-hand drive in South Africa during the 1960s and up until 1972 and sold locally as the Chrysler Valiant.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] All South African models were built with a locally sourced 225 cu in six-cylinder engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Plymouth/Dodge models were fully replaced by Australian Chrysler products from 1972.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dodge Dart started being produced in Brazil from knock-down kits in October 1969, replacing the Simca-derived Chrysler Esplanada.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Production of A-body Darts continued in Brazil, where they were also sold as Charger, Magnum and Le Baron, through 1981 and in Colombia through 1977.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Dart-based A-body cars with various names including Valiant, Coronado and Polara were produced in Argentina through 1979.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Brazilian A-body cars used the 111-inch wheelbase (2,820 mm) bodystyle from 1970 and were always equipped with the 318 cubic inch V8, set up to run on the lower-octane fuel used in Latin America at the time.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Originally a three-speed manual transmission was standard, with an optional Torqueflite automatic transmission, and later a four-speed manual was also available.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The equipment levels in Brazil were: Sedan de Luxo, Coupe de Luxo, SE, Gran Sedan, Gran Coupe, Charget LS, Le Baron and Magnum with the sporty Charger R/T .
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The last true A-body Dart was built in the summer of 1981 in Brazil.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] This car is virtually identical to the U.S. market's 1976 Swinger.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] From 1965 to 1970 a Spanish version of the Dodge Dart based on the original from the United States was manufactured in the Barreiros Villaverde factory in Madrid.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] In 1969, the Barreiros-made Dart was facelifted with a different front fascia; using the same headlights from Dodge C-38 trucks.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] In March 1971 a new version, using the same 111 in (2,819 mm) wheelbase but with different sheet metal, the Dodge 3700 was produced until 1977 when the Spanish automotive taxation system was changed.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The 3700 actually received the sheet metal from the Argentinian Dodge Polara, with certain modifications for the Spanish market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The rear wheel openings were larger and round, the grille and all lights were different, as was the instrumentation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The 3700 also came as standard with front disc brakes and power steering.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] A total of 17,589 units were manufactured of the earlier range (1965 to 1970) in Spain, they were produced as a SKD due to the protectionist Spanish regulations of those years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] 9,959 Dodge 3700s were built until 1977, although the last new 3700 was only first registered in 1980.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dart and the 3700 were the biggest national production car available in Spain during all production years.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] It was an expensive luxury car with very low fuel economy by Spanish standards.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Nonetheless, it was considered an economic car for its size in those few markets to which it was exported.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] In Switzerland, for instance, it was priced exactly the same as a V8-engined American-built four-door Dodge Dart Custom and had only slightly less power, but was taxed considerably less.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] These vehicles were also exported to other European markets such as France and the United Kingdom but without much success.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Spanish Dodges never met sales goals and was an expensive failure for the Barreiros concern.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The break-even point was 5,000 cars per year, a goal which was only surpassed once, in 1966.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Barreiros brothers were forced to sell off the company which was reorganized as Chrysler España, S.A.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dodge Dart GL was a luxury model, while the GT was the sporty version.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The base version has a three-speed manual transmission, while the GT came with either a four-speed manual or a three-speed automatic - this was the same unit as the one mounted in the Chrysler 2 L.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The gasoline Darts had the biggest engine ever mounted into a mass-produced car in Spain, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Chrysler slant-six engine.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The "3700" number is a reference to the 3.7 litres of displacement.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] No other six-cylinder engine car has been produced as much in Spain.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] A diesel Dart (named "Barreiros diesel") was also produced.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] These models, mainly intended for taxi use, were very basic and very slow.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] They have 7-inch round headlamps rather than the large oblong units on fancier Spanish Darts, and use the round taillights from the first generation Simca 1000.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The engine was the Barreiros C65, a 2,007 cc (122.5 cu in) inline-four with 65 PS (48 kW) at 4,500 rpm.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Top speed was claimed to be 124 km/h (77 mph).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Production of Spanish Dodges stopped in 1977.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Peugeot bought the Villaverde factory, as Chrysler was divesting their European operations in Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Spanish Dodges were popular with members of the Spanish government during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco was killed on 20 December 1973 while traveling in his Dodge 3700 GT.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] On 12 June 1975, Fernando Herrero Tejedor, the Minister Secretary General of the Movimiento Nacional and the politician mentoring Adolfo Suárez, died in a car accident while travelling in his official Dodge 3700 in the municipality of Adanero.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Peugeot would not market another large car in Spain similar to the size of the Dart (the previous Chrysler 180 was smaller) until the Talbot Tagora came out in 1980, albeit without much success.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Although being the only large Dodge produced locally in Spain, previous American models such as the Coronet and Meadowbrook were exported to Spain ever since the 1950s with moderate success.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dart name (rather than Aspen) was applied to Dodge-branded F-body cars in Mexico, corresponding to the Mexican Chrysler-branded F-body cars badged as Valiant Volare (without the "é" in the "Volare" nameplate).
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] It was a downscale (lower price, cheaper trim) version of the American Dodge 600 4-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Dart K 2-door and wagon models were sold alongside the Dart E until 1988 and the old SOHC I-4 2.2 L engine was replaced by the new 2.5 L I-4 for the 1987 season.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] These were the last new cars in the world to bear the Dodge Dart name until its revival in 2013.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dart name was dropped when Chrysler de México introduced the Spirit in 1990.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Dodge Dart was sold alongside its replacement for part of the 1976 model year before it was discontinued in the U.S. and Canadian markets.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Over its original 13-year production run, the Dart earned a good reputation.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] "The Dart was one of the most successful compact cars ever introduced in the American automobile marketplace," according to R.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The A-body Dart was replaced by the F-body Dodge Aspen in late spring of 1976, alongside the somewhat larger M-body Dodge Diplomat (which was seen as a high end mid-size car or even a low end full-size car that was positioned between the Aspen and St.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] Nevertheless, as these cars were considerably too large for the compact car market, that segment would be occupied by the Omni for Dodge to compete in a rapidly changing automobile market.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Aspen was replaced in 1980 by the Dodge Aries and the Dodge 400 in 1982.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] These models would then be succeeded by the Dodge Spirit and later by the Stratus and Avenger sedans.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Diplomat would be produced until 1989 when it was replaced by the full-size Monaco and then the Intrepid.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] The Intrepid was then replaced by the Dodge Charger sedan.
[src:chrysler-a-platform/dodge-dart-p02] After 35 years, the Dodge Dart (PF) was resurrected for the 2013 model year as a nameplate in the domestic market to replace the Caliber as Dodge's compact passenger car.
